Content: Discount broker is a stockbroker or brokerage firm that charges a reduced commission on transactions but typically does not provide investment advice or other services.

Jargon: Common Stock

A share of COMMON STOCK is a single share of ownership in a corporation available for purchase on most trading platforms. If a company has 500 shares in total, then owning five shares would make you a 1% owner of the company.

KEY ADVANTAGES:
1. Ownership in a company so you can brag that you are part owner in Tesla.
2. Voting rights! You can tell your friends: “Well maybe that’s how Elon feels but I’m going to have a word with him. Technically, I’m his boss!”
3. Eligible for dividend payouts. Mr. Wonderful’s momma always told him to hold dividend-yielding stocks.

Common stock is indeed a tangible asset as discussed yesterday.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-03

Jargon: Preferred Stock

A share of STOCK in a corporation that comes with no voting rights but has a preference in terms of dividend payments and liquidation.

KEY ADVANTAGES:
1. Dividends get paid out first (versus common). Dividend payouts are also calculated differently than common stock but this is a topic for a different time.
2. If a company goes bankrupt, chances are common shareholders will get nothing. Preferred holders get priority (but bond-holders come first).
3. Preferred shares are CALLABLE. We’ll cover this later.

DISADVANTAGES:
1. No voting rights.
2. There is interest rate risk (we’ll cover this later too) on preferred stock, due to how the dividends are paid out.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-03

Jargon: Dividend


A dividend is the distribution of some of a company’s earnings to its shareholders, as determined by the company’s board of directors.

1. Some people like div-paying stocks since you’ll actually see a return on your investment, whereas non-div-paying stocks are a guess whether the stock prices will go up or down.

2. Dividends are usually paid out as cash but may also be paid out as stock.
3. There is a date called the “ex-div date”. As long as you own the dividend prior to that date, you’ll receive dividends at the payout date.
4. Preferred stock dividends are calculated differently than common stock dividends.


MORE BRAIN FOOD:
When a company announces an upcoming div payment the “good news” will cause the stock price to rise. When the dividend is paid out, the shares will drop a bit since the div payment is coming off the company’s balance sheet.

There is a type of trading called “div trading” which is dedicated to this (we will cover when we get to trading strategies).

Div trading is WAY more popular in the UK than in the US

Jargon: Bull & Bear

Bull: A BULL is someone who purchases shares now because they believe the price will go up.
Bear: A BEAR is someone who sells shares now, hoping to buy them back in the future since they expect the prices to drop.
You might hear people say “I’m bullish on Bitcoin” or “I hear Goldman is bearish on GME”.

Author: Tarun_17#4341

Day-05

Jargon: Liquidity

“Liquidity is how quickly an asset can be converted into cash.”

We say “cash” since cash is technically the most liquid of all assets – it can be used AT IT’S VALUE to purchase pretty much anything you need.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-06

Jargon: Bid, Ask, and Bid-Ask Spread

Bid: The amount of money a buyer is willing to pay for each share of a given stock.

Ask The amount of money the seller is willing to accept for each share of a given stock.

Bid-Ask-Spread: The difference between the two.
 
Following up from Yesterday's Jargon: Stocks with very narrow spreads are quite LIQUID while stocks with very wide spreads are ILLIQUID.

Can you see why?
 
Example of BID/ASK: ITC is being quoted at Rs.100/Rs.101
The buyer will pay the ASK price of Rs.101.
The seller will receive the BID price of Rs.100.
 
So where does that extra Rs.1 go?
Why it goes to tomorrow’s word of the day!

Jargon: Market Maker

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-08

Jargon: Blue Chip Stock

A Blue Chip Stock is a stock in a company that is extremely successful, typically with a market cap in the billions and an amazing reputation.

But wait, there’s more!

Blue Chip Stocks also:

1. Typically pay dividends, some have been doing so for DECADES
2. If “Blue Chip” was a bond categorization it would likely be AA+
3. Blue Chips tend to recover relatively swiftly after market downturns
4. Some popular Blue Chips: Coca-Cola, Wal-Mart, IBM, etc.

Fun Fact!

“Blue Chips” got their name from the game Poker where the blue chips are typically worth the most.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-09

Jargon: Long vs Short

“Long” or “being long” means you are bullish about a stock so you buy shares and hold them for a period of time, anticipating that the stock will rise in value and you will be able to sell your shares later for a profit.

What if you anticipate a stock will FALL in value? How can you profit off that?

Here is how you SHORT a stock:
1. Pick a stock you believe will fall in value.
2. Borrow the stock from an entity (usually you will pay a small fee for doing this).
3. Sell the stock to a 3rd party.
4. Wait until the stock falls.
5. Buy the stock back.
6. Return it back to the entity you borrowed it from.


Overly simplified example:
1. AAPL is currently trading at $100. Bob believes AAPL will drop in price.
2. Bob goes out and borrows 10 shares from JPMorgan (let’s assume no fee for this example).
3. Bob sells those 10 shares on the stock market for a total of $1,000.
4. AAPL falls a week later to $50 per share.
5. Bob buys 10 shares on the market for $500.
6. Bob returns the 10 shares to JPMorgan, and pockets the extra $500.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-10

Jargon: IPO

An IPO or Initial Public Offering is the first sale or offering of a stock by a company to the public. An IPO occurs when a company decides to go public rather than remain solely owned by private or inside investors.

Why go public?

1. Allows the company to raise capital from public investors
2. Early investors, executives, and in some cases many employees get to
“cash in” on the shares of the company that they have been holding
3. Liquidity for investors is increased

Some More Tidbits:

Usually, at least one large investment bank is nominated as an underwriter
to bring the company public. It’s a pretty big honor (and paycheck) so there is
a lot of negotiating before the lead underwriter is selected
Going public means your company is going to be under SEC scrutiny going
forward

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-11

Jargon: Stock Exchange

A stock exchange is a location where stockbrokers and traders can buy and sell shares in a company. 

These companies are PUBLIC as discussed yesterday, so trading happening behind closed doors wouldn’t be very fair to other potential investors.

The five largest stock exchanges in the world are:

1. New York Stock Exchange:  $28 Trillion
2. Nasdaq:           $13 Trillion
3. Japan Stock Exchange:    $5 Trillion
4. Shanghai Stock Exchange:  $5 Trillion
5. Hong Kong Stock Exchange: $4 Trillion

There are exchanges that trade other securities as well, but for today we are discussing just stock exchanges.

Some cool facts:

Exchanges used to be in physical locations. Ever seen those epic videos of people shouting at each other in a crowded room holding sheets of paper? Those were physical exchanges.
Now, trading is ALMOST all done electronically (Nasdaq was the first electronic exchange!).
If a stock on the NYSE has an average 30-day trading price of below $1, it gets delisted from the exchange!

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-12

Jargon: Pink Sheets

Pink sheets are stocks that are not listed on any public stock exchanges, they trade over-the-counter.

Pink sheets are sometimes referred to as “penny stocks” because they are so cheap, usually due to the small market capsize of the company.

Depending on the exchange requirements, usually, pink sheets are not listed on an exchange because their price per share is simply too low, most often less than $3-$4.

Since there is very little regulation on pink sheets, they are very risky, but due to their volatile nature, it is possible for some PS stocks to see incredible growth in a short period of time. There are firms that have capitalized on this.

Most brokerage-related movies often show scenes of brokers trying to push PS stocks to uneducated investors, claiming that due to the low prices the upside is incredible (meanwhile the brokers make a killing on fees).

Penny stocks are called “pink sheets” because the listings were originally printed on pink paper. Now they are published electronically but are still listed as “OTC PINK”.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-13

Jargon: Volatility

Google Definition: Volatility is the liability to change rapidly and unpredictably, especially for the worse.

Investopedia Definition: In finance, volatility is the degree of variation of a trading price series over time, usually measured by the standard deviation of logarithmic returns.

Volatility is usually measured using standard deviation, which indicates how tightly the price of a stock is clustered around the mean.

Simply put, volatility is how “jumpy” a stock is. If a stock is slow to move either up or down it’s not very volatile.

The statistics behind volatility, how it’s calculated, and how it helps technical traders are pretty vast and we will certainly not go into that here, but it is one of the most exciting measures of stock for quant traders. 

We’ll be covering much more jargon that has the word “volatile” not too far in the future.

When people on the desk say “vol” this is what they are referring to, not volume!

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-14

Jargon: Sector

A sector is an industry or market that shares common operating characteristics.

“Technology” is a sector.

“Health Care” is a sector.

Often you’ll find that stocks within a sector have related stock price movements.

For example, say there was an alien invasion and these aliens ate METAL for food. They started eating all the metal on Earth.

The automobile sector would likely see a significant drop in value.

In other words, most automobile stocks (Nissan, Toyota, Tesla, etc.) would see their stock price DROP significantly.

Traders would imagine that because metal is now so rare, car manufacturers will have to charge a lot more for each vehicle, which will in turn cause fewer cars to be sold.

This is bad for the car companies and their stock price would drop as a result.

Fun Fact:
Is TSLA an automobile company? For years many banks just weren’t sure. Some had TSLA as an Auto company while other banks had TSLA as a Tech stock. TSLA has even dabbled in the Energy sector!

Most companies are pretty straightforward, but sometimes such a revolutionary company can sometimes confuse the pros!

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-15

Jargon: Global Industry Classification Standard

“GICS” or Global Industry Classification Standard is an industry taxonomy developed in 1999 by MSCI and S&P for use by the global financial community. GICS consists of 11 sectors, 24 industry groups, 69 industries, and 158 sub-industries.

(Thank you very much Wiki dear)

Ok, so what did all that fancy talk mean?

We discussed SECTOR yesterday. But what if Goldman calls it “Autos” and Morgan Stanley calls it “Cars”. What if Goldman has a second level breakdown under Autos called “Gas, Electric, and Self-Sustaining” while Morgan only has “Powered, and Self-Sustaining” 

Having each firm decide all levels of sector classifications can get messy very quickly, and it makes it near impossible to share data between firms.

Let’s say Citi hires DTCC to clean their trades, but DTCC returns the trades with their OWN sector classifications which don’t fit into the Citi system?

Enter GICS.

It’s universal; nearly everyone in finance is on GICS already.

FUN FACT:
When GICS decides to update their sectors it costs firms in some cases MILLIONS of dollars to do testing and updates to all of their systems and data.

All this commotion from something that sounds like an ice cream flavor…

Content:
Day-16

Jargon: Volume & Average Daily Traded Volume

Volume is a count of how many shares of stock have traded during a trading period.

When talking raw volume, usually it just means how much was traded over the course of a day.

ADTV is “Average Daily Traded Volume” which is a popular metric used to see how liquid a stock has been trading over a time period.

Let’s take the most popular version of ADTV:
“ADTV22” AKA “The one-month average daily trading volume”.

Let’s pretend we have a fairly illiquid stock called QZT.

If QZT traded 100 shares each day for 21 days, and then for the last day it traded 50,000 shares, what would the ADTV22 be?

((100 * 21) + (50000 * 1)) / 22 = 2,368 shares a day on average.

You can see the weakness for doing this for illiquid stocks such as this unusual case. It doesn’t tell the full story; this stock looks quite liquid but really it just had one great day!

For your average liquid stock, this metric works just fine.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-17

Jargon: Index

An index is a method by which to measure the performance of a group of assets. Some indices are very broad such as the S&P 500 or the Dow Jones, while others are much narrower such as the S&P GSCI Energy & Metals index.

You can think of an index as a basket of securities that helps you understand how a certain sector is performing.

Most people use an index to help them track how their investment is doing “relative to an index”.

For example, if you are pretty sure that Honda is doing a great job at manufacturing new vehicles so you invest heavily, you might want to track your investment versus an auto index to see how your pick stacks up against autos in general.

Not only do indices track sectors, but there are even country-based indices!

Another great use for indices is diverse investing. If you only have a couple of thousand dollars to invest, it might be tricky to diversify your portfolio. Buying into funds that track popular diverse indices (such as the S&P or DJ), could be a great way to diversify at a low cost.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-18

Jargon: ETF

An Exchange Traded Fund (ETF), is a security that is comprised of a basket of securities built to track an index, sector, commodity, bonds, or any asset
quite frankly. ETFs can be bought and sold on a stock exchange just like the underlying securities!

Big banks often construct ETFs to follow certain investment strategies (not even a specific index or sector in particular), and offer them to their PB
clients to invest in.


One of the most popular ETFs is the SPDR S&P 500 ETF which trades by the ticker SPY. This tracks the S&P 500.

ETF popularity has skyrocketed in the past two decades. In 2003, worldwide ETF assets equaled $204Bn. By 2020 that number had reached $7.7Tr !!

Did you know?
People love buying ETFs because to get the same level of diversification, you would have to buy all of the underlying components individually which aside from being quite cumbersome and expensive also costs quite a lot on brokerage commissions. With ETFs, it’s significantly cheaper!

Author: Srishti#0907
Content:
Hi Keshav
That's quite a question! From what I understand, feelings direct our thoughts. We are constantly driven to find an explanation to what we see or feel and that's where thoughts come into the picture. 

For example, a person performing on stage gets jitters backstage. A confident person would be feeling good so he will call it excitement. But a person who's not confident would be feeling negative so he might call it nervousness. And then our thoughts spiral down.

If you want to read further this might help: https://www.futurelearn.com/info/blog/thinking-and-feeling-whats-the-difference 

Also programming your subconscious is like building muscle memory, you can remind yourself to think in a certain way - how does benefit me, how can I overcome this challenge - and soon that is how your mindset will become. 

Hope this helps! You might find our "Fundamentals" section interesting

Author: Prashant Jindal#5435
Content:
Another reply from Akshit who is an IIM Calcutta passout-

So getting data from the client is one of the most important parts of solving a problem. Typically, you'll get a whole dump of data from the client and there will be too much noise to directly go ahead with your analysis. You'll need to narrow it down yourself and identify the useful parts. The backoffices do less problem solving compared to the consultants, they usually support with things such as visualising data. The backoffices can also assist with background research, competitor analysis etc. But direct client interactions, getting data, etc. are part of your day-to-day work. For example, on my present project, we typically find out what data we need through interviews with the client's departments. We use those interviews to build hypotheses that we then try to back up with data.

Author: Explorin#4311
Content:
Hey,

I would follow the following approach:

Goal 1 - Identify the primary steps in the user flow

Goal 2 - Once you have identified all the steps, its time to perform detailed analysis of each step to figure out all the probable actions that a user might take.

Goal 3 - Now, piece all steps together to create an overall user flow ( consider all possibilities ). The aim is to draw the user journey flow chart.
 

PS: "Step" here refers to a process that will lead users to take a specific action. Practically speaking, there can be multiple user pathways. So, your focus should be to identify the pieces of a puzzle --> then know all of them --> Successfully piece them together in multiple ways

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-19

Jargon: Arbitrage

Arbitrage is an opportunity to make free money by taking advantage of a price discrepancy for the same asset.

A really simple example would be if XYZ stock sold on both NASDAQ and NYSE. On NASDAQ the stock was trading for $99 a share and on NYSE, $100 per share.

You could buy 100 shares on NASDAQ for $9,900 and instantly flip the shares on NYSE for $10,000 making $100 profit completely risk-free.

This is known as Pure Arbitrage.

Risk Arbitrage is similar, but it’s with a bit of a gamble included so you could potentially be wrong and end up losing.

Arbitrage used to exist but in practice it is VERY difficult for regular retail investors to take advantage of these opportunities nowadays since market makers have powerful algos seeking and taking advantage of these the moment they exist, closing the gap instantly.

Arbitrage isn’t just about stocks, it could also work across multiple assets.

For example, you could purchase an asset in one country and sell it in another where there is a mismatch in currency exchange rates.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-20

Jargon: Asset Class

We already discussed “asset” (our first jargon). There are tangible and intangible assets.

We defined stocks (common and preferred), but there are many other assets.

The official online definition of the asset class is:

“An asset class is a grouping of investments that exhibit similar characteristics and are subject to the same laws and regulations.”

Each “type” of asset is in a class of its own, hence “asset class”.

Stocks are part of the EQUITY asset class.

This is because when you own a stock you own equity in a company.

Over the next week, we’ll break down the other popular asset classes.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-21

Jargon: Cash and Cash Equivalent

The important thing to know about this asset class is that it is the most liquid of all asset classes.

From a regulatory perspective, this is an extremely important asset class for big banks as they might need some extra cash on hand quickly if some of their more risky trades turn sour.

Often this asset class is also turned to when a party needs to post collateral.

So what can be liquidated quickly?

> Cash
> Govt Bonds
> Commercial Paper

From an accounting perspective, cash and cash equivalents help companies with their working capital needs since these liquid assets are used to pay off current liabilities, which are short-term debts and bills.

You’re generally not expecting amazing returns from this asset class. Unlike other asset classes, its purpose is those mentioned above, not to earn profits.

A few items in this definition we did not cover yet, but we will shortly: Collateral, regulatory, Govt Bonds, Commercial Paper, working capital, current liabilities.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-22

Jargon: Alternative Investments

We already covered the major asset classes: Equity, Fixed Income, Cash, or Cash Equivalent.

There are quite a few additional asset classes but most institutions don’t agree on how to categorize them.

Some institutions put them all in a catch-all bucket called “Alternative Investments”, while some institutions categorize them individually.

Since I would like to move on to new topics I’m going to bucket them here as well.

Here are a few asset classes that might fall in the alternative bucket or might stand on their own:

1. Real Estate – Land & Property
2. Commodities – Gold, Minerals, Oil, Grains, Beef, etc.
3. Cryptocurrency – Bitcoin, ETH, Dogecoin, Potcoin, etc.
4. Art – Paintings, sculptors, etc.
5. Private Equity
…and more

Most analytic-driven firms won’t bucket all of these into one “Alternatives” bucket because commodities are affected by seasonality while art is not. Bucketing like this isn’t very safe for making assumptions about investments or risks given how different these asset classes are.

Another example: Real estate is a very stable investment. Crypto is more erratic than Goofy on drugs.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-23

Jargon: Bonds

A bond is a fixed income instrument. It’s a loan made by YOU the “bondholder” to a corporation or government “the issuer” to help them raise money for use in their company or government. This is paid back either slowly over time or as a lump sum, often many years later.

***Storytime***

Zapple Computing is excited to release its latest offering the iBalloon, a balloon that streams both party streamers AND music! Sadly, they have run out of funds for manufacturing. Already pretty diluted, they don’t want to offer up any more equity of the company (stock issuance) to raise capital, so instead, they offer YOU, Jane Doe, a BOND in exchange for a gazillion dollars.

They then use the gazillion dollars and invest it all in their iBalloon product which is a colossal failure.

The company goes bankrupt and you never see a penny back on your gazillion dollar investment.

Sad times.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-24

Jargon: Zero Coupon Bond

As discussed above, a bond is a loan from you (the bondholder) to an entity that gets paid back to you at some point in the future.

The simplest bond to understand both conceptually and mathematically is the zero-coupon bond.

It’s simply a loan paid back in the future at a higher amount.

There are no intermediate interest payments.

Example: A $1,000 bond that expires in one year is trading for $900 today.

Essentially it’s as if you invested your $900 and earned 11% interest over the year, a very nice return on investment.

There is a pretty substantial risk to consider though. What if this bond pays out not in 1 but in 10 years.

You won’t see a penny until the expiration date, which is a long time to “hope” that the company or gov’t doesn’t go bankrupt! If they do go under, there is a chance you won’t see your money.


Fun Fact!
You DO have to pay taxes (federal, state, and local), on the money you earn on the bond (in this case a total of $100). In some cases, you’ll have to pay taxes on the interest that you have earned throughout the bond period EVEN THOUGH YOU DIDN’T GET A PAYOUT YET.

Pretty weird.

There are ways around this but we won’t get into this today.

Author: Explorin#4311
Content:
Reading Day 3 done

Principal insight: Read a chapter on types of thinking devised by Chanakya. Following are the various ways of thinking I came across today:

1. Both-Side thinking: Considering pros and cons, i.e. both sides of the coin in every situation. 

2. Alternative thinking: Choosing one way of thinking from Sama, Dana, Bheda, Danda based on the person or situation you are dealing with

3. Leadership Thinking: driven by the laws of selflessness, such a thought process is unleashed only in Kings, whose true source of happiness lies in the happiness of his people. It is an all-inclusive thinking which encompasses the living and non-living, 
such as animals, birds, plants, minerals, water and all else parts of the kingdom.

4. Creative thinking: He says creativity is perfectly executed when decisions taken are based on right time and right timing.

5. Lateral thinking: Thinking out of box, while ensuring the existence of the box. Sometimes we get trapped in our own illusions.

6. Spiritual Thinking: Highest form of thinking, which means to be in tune with the laws of nature through a state of awareness. While practising this thinking, you follow the path of dharma. Dharma denotes various ideas and concepts - morality, ethics, duty, responsibility and spirituality 

Learning: To do spiritual good while enjoying the wordly and creating material well-being requires a balance in your thinking, which greatly comes through Meditation. As described in this book, Meditation is the process of controlling flow of thoughts and calming the mind.

Author: Keshav Bidawatka#6333
Content:
Wonderful work @argus. The hard work you have put into is vividly visible through your work.

Suggestions from my side are:
1. The first steps in solving a Product problem is defining the objective( the metric which we want to move) and understanding the users.  I thought that you didn't define these concretely

Understanding the users: you only listed that they are 1st/2nd year students. Try to be more exhaustive about who they are, what are their motivations, problems,.. Here, here you are free to create multiple user personas.

Objective: "improving the user experience" is an abstract objective, try to define your objective as something which is concrete and can be measured. for eg: acquisition, engagement( time spent on the platform+ discord), course completion rate,..

2. List the problems that the users face before thinking about the improvements.

This would make you think more exhaustively about problems. Otherwise directly jumping to the improvements makes you biased and you might miss some problems which they face.

3. Loved how you hypothesized and validated improvements 3 and 4. The only problem was that you gave solutions for improvements 1 and 2 beforehand, so the structure went for a toss. First validate all the problems and then give solutions together.
4. Give the reasons why you assumed one improvement to be more impactful/effort than the other. I know it's the hard part but giving proper reasoning would enhance your clarity of the goal you decided in the first step.

Author: sourabkumar004#1267
Content:
Hey @argus good work buddy.
@Keshav Bidawatka gave a lot of to-the-point feedbacks.

Here are a few feedbacks from my side.
1. The most important point, everyone might know the solution, the catch is how well can you present it. Also, don't assume anything that the person reading/evaluating might know.
Structure your thoughts, and structure your presentation.
A few more things you should have covered:
1. Who are the users?: Mentioning the users is fine, but who are they. You shouldn't assume that anyone reading knows the traits. Explain them better to set the expectation about your target user base so that they follow you across the submission easily.

2. Add a why for everything. If you are proposing something, add WHY for every proposed recommendation.

3. Cover metrics of measurement, and how will you define is your recommendation ends up being a success, or becomes a failure.

Remember, these are suggestions, and you might have a different perspective. If so, would love to discuss and hear you out.

1. Lust - Overindulgence in anything 
2. Anger - Losing our temper
3. Greed - Wanting more than what is required 
4. Pride - Overpossessiveness
5. Arrogance - Giving too much importance to oneself
6. Foolhardiness - the quality of being reckless

Observation: The ancient wisdom is timeless and is supposedly the source of the all branches of sciences. So, explore it to unleash yourself

Author: vedant11#6910
Content:
Both of them look good in general
I'm not a designer nor a front-end specialist
But I'll tell what I think

things I liked:
table:
- good background choice
- proportions of logo and table seems proper enough
- adding border radius is a good choice in modern design terms since it gives a natural look
form:
- I think you went for  sweet large black buttons with white text fields, that'd look sweet

can add finishing:
- top margin could've been added
table: 
- width of the table spanning the complete page seems a bit off. Usually people want to move their eyes only a bit. 
- modern designs are usually a bit 'flat' looking rather than 3-d looking; slim borders and no/soft shadows will avoid giving it a 3-d look
-  Probably, black border on an orange button isn't the best choice; such details add up to give things unprofessional look
- margin between two columns can either be completely eliminated or increased a bit. Looks bit off, personally. 
-small but bold texts get hard to read on low-res screens
form:
- width vs height ratio could've been more natural, I think
- left aligned placeholder texts would give your form a look that it's narrower
- again, padding between the Submit button and last field would be great

Author: vedant11#6910
Content:
Continuing with day 1
Started technical reading
- encryption techniques and applications
- let's say A sent B a padlock and A kept the key with it. B attached a box and locked it (locking doesn't require a key). The parcel is sent back to A and only by using the key, can A access the content of the box. This is how private and public keys are used. Public keys are used to validate that the padlock belongs to A, in this case

Author: Keshav Bidawatka#6333
Content:
Wrote something on what I observed yesterday: 

"The world is moving very fast. We are always surrounded by electronic devices which crave for our attention. We are trying to engage ourselves or do something every second of the waking hour.

Bamboozled as to where I am leading?

It is that digital noises have infiltrated our normal every day conversations with people around us. 

Haven't you been frustrated when someone you are talking to starts surfing his/her phone? Or you are sitting in a room where two of your friends are watching noisy reels.

This destroys the essence of the whole conversation by diminishing our ability to think and have deep conversations, which is a double-edged sword.

So, be in an environment where healthy distraction-less conversations happen. You would feel energized there instead of being drained."

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Day-01:

Reading: A Practical Guide to Quantitative Finance Interviews

Chapter-01: General Principals

5 General Principals that will be extremely useful for Quant Interviews

1) Build a Broad Knowledge Base:
    Usually, quant is classified as a problem solver, so a basic understanding of a 
    broad range of topics often helps in better analyzing problems, so the 
    interviewer expects us to have broad knowledge in Maths, Finance, and 
    Programming
2) Practice your Interview Skills:
     Prepare yourself for potential questions long before you enter an interview 
     room
3) Listen Carefully: 
   It helps us to understand the problem well before we attempt to answer them, 
   Interviewer doesn't expect a complete solution, rather focuses on our approach 
   in solving the problem
4) Speak your Mind:
     Conver your analysis to the interviewer, which indeed creates an opportunity 
     for the interviewer to correct the mistakes in our approach If any
5) Make reasonable assumptions:
     In Quant job, you are unlikely to have all the necessary information or data 
     you'd prefer to have before you build a model or a decision
     So, it is advisable to make reasonable assumptions and design appropriate 
     frameworks to solve problems

Read one of the best phrase of the book it says,
**"We can be blind to the obvious, and we are also blind to our blindness.”**

We do stuff like that every day. We get so focused on what we think is important that we fail to see the really big stuff  that’s threatening to derail us, whether it’s social media, or  the latest technological advances, or  the rise of the millennials, or whatever. We’re too often focused on the wrong stuff.
Pick your heads up, people. Look around. Notice the new stuff  because there’s an awfully lot of important new stuff out there to notice. Pay attention to it. Study it. Learn it.

Author: Keshav Bidawatka#6333
Content:
I have a knack for embracing, observing, and living the stupidest of occurrences which bring a smile to my face.

Don’t believe me? Here you go:

For quite some days I’m observing how we walk in a group of friends in campus. The group usually divides into a number of dynamic subgroups with some finding themselves walking alone. So the solo ones are constantly in a hunt to find spaces in a subgroup to walk and interact with. This leads to some other guy getting eliminated from the subgroup, who in turn tries to rejoin or join another XD.

This happens on a loop and it becomes an unconscious game of finding horizontal friends from the group to walk and be engaged with. 

What are your stupid observations while walking in a group?

Author: Keshav Bidawatka#6333
Content:
Sharing a piece of wisdom which @Explorin shared with me:

Let's start with a question.
Tell me below how’s your life going. Are you satisfied and happy?

If not, don’t fret. Everybody faces problems. Anger, frustration, anxiety, and all the other emotions which arise with problems are a part and byproduct of life.

And if you think that the problems or negative emotions which you are going through are only plaguing you, then you are wrong. Firstly, people around you might not be sharing that problem openly. Secondly, even if people around you aren’t facing that problem, there’s a larger world out there flooded with people you don’t know.

So, treat your problem as a community problem. Fuel your motivation to solve the problem by solving it for you as well as others. Talk to your mentors about it and dig into the depths of the problem. 

After all even startups germinate from founders trying to solve the problems they were personally distressed by.

Author: Keshav Bidawatka#6333
Content:
A week back, I along with my 5 friends went to a fast-food restaurant to exclusively eat Waffle.

After eating, while asking for the bill, the owner pitched trying something like Pizza. This brought water in the mouth of one of my friends.

Seeing the opportunity, the owner started convincing by highlighting the little differential between the old bill amount and the new bill amount after buying a pizza. He even calculated the little amount each one of us would cost with that extra pizza.

So, in the end, we agreed to order it.
Two learnings from the witty owner:

**1. Business instincts:** He caught the opportunity to ramp up the pitch seeing the vulnerability of my friend and came with a convincing argument about how the extra pizza only costs Rs 30 per person.

**2. You gotta show the product to the users: **If you aren’t able to, the quality of your product doesn’t matter. 
The owner knew that students here usually order from Dominos or Pizza Hut. So, this was his chance to show us his pizza. 

Additionally, If we wished to revisit only for waffles, it would be less frequent, but if we liked the pizza, we were more likely to visit again and more frequently.

Think And Grow Rich(ch-8 , decision)

Insight-
It's better to arrive at a decision quickly and then change it slowly, rather than taking a lot of time to make decisions and then quickly changing it, if influenced by someone. This doesn't mean that we can make decisions abruptly without thinking. 
Any decision backed by strong desire has a tendency to transmute itself into its physical equivalent.
Indecision is a habit which stops one from reaching a decision and the person ends up following someone else's decision or advice. In such cases there is no internal motivation.

Author: anuj#7534
Content: The R.A.I.N. Technique for meditation: Recognize. Allow. Investigate. Non-identification. 1) Recognize: Acknowledge your feelings. 2) Allow: Where you lean into the pain. Let the pain be. 3) Investigate: Check out how the situation is impacting your body. Is my face hot? Is my back tight? Etc. 4) Non-identification: Realize that just because you feel pain or frustration or guilt or anger right now does not mean you are an angry or broken person. It is simply a phase happening at this moment, not your identity as a person.

Author: radhajayaraman#0544
Content:
hi guys! Just want to share a quick productivity plus growth idea that I came across sometime ago. 
Its based on the idea of weekly reviews on onself. Basically a granular self introspection spanned over weeks. I'd suggest that you create a table (excel preferably) and try to answer these three questions by the end of every week( say  sunday afternoon). 
1. What went well last week?
2. What didn't go well?
3. What changes do I need make to make this week better?

You'll find yourself thinking quite hard for first few weeks for the changes but it'll b a fun activity. Also when you see this table at the end of every week, seeing how far you've come, your happy moments and things you need to work on will make you quite satisfied about yourself. 

Hope this helps! I've been working on this too! 
Cheers! 🌷
@everyone

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
How to make scanning of my design easier?
1.    CONVENTIONS ARE YOUR FRIENDS: 
(a) It is recommended to innovate when we know we have a better idea, but take advantage of conventions when we don’t. This recommendation needs to be kept in mind along with the fact that something creative, innovative and original is generally encouraged.
(b)CLARITY TRUMPS CONSISTENCY: If we can make something significantly clearer by making it slightly inconsistent, choose in favor of clarity.
2.    CREATE EFFECTIVE VISUAL HIERARCHIES:
For grasping information instantly, effective visual hierarchies are essential. It is attained by adding following traits to our design: 
(a) The more important something is, the more prominent it is. (For ex, make important elements bolder, larger, visible)
(b) Things that are related logically are related visually. (For ex, similar things can be grouped together under a heading under same visual style.)
(c) Things are “nested” visually to show what’s part of what.
3.    BREAK UP PAGES INTO CLEARLY DEFINED AREAS:
Dividing the page into clearly defined areas is important because it allows users to decide quickly which areas of the page to focus on and which areas they can safely ignore. 
4.    MAKE IT OBVIOUS WHAT’S CLICKABLE:
Users should not get confused with what’s clickable and what’s not clickable.
5.    KEEP THE NOISE DOWN TO DULL ROAR:
One of the great enemies of easy-to-grasp pages is visual noise. The different kinds of noise are:
(a)SHOUTING: Shouting is the result of a failure to make tough decisions about which elements are really the most important. Use hierarchies to eliminate it.
(b)DISORGANIZATION: It indicates things strewn everywhere. Use of grid to align elements can help.
(c)CLUTTER: It refers too much stuff. Elimination of less important things can work to get rid of excess content.
FORMAT TEXT TO SUPPORT SCANNING:
Use plenty of headings, keep paragraphs short, use bulleted lists, highlight key terms for scan-friendly text.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
CHAPTER-04
KRUG’S SECOND LAW OF USABILITY:
It doesn’t matter how many times I have to click, as long as each click is a mindless, unambiguous choice. Users don’t mind a lot of clicks as long as each click is painless and they have continued confidence that they’re on the right track.
SCENT OF INFORMATION:
Links that clearly and unambiguously identify their target give off a strong scent that assures users that clicking them will bring them nearer to their “prey.” 
ANIMAL, VEGETABLE OR MINERAL?
It refers to the idea that as long as you accept the premise that anything that’s not a plant or an animal fall under “mineral,” it requires almost no thought to answer the question correctly.
GO FOR EASY CHOICES:
For instance, making an initial selection takes you to another screen where you see only the relevant questions or information for that selection. 
SOME ASSISTANCE MAY BE REQUIRED IN CASE OF DIFFICULT CHOICES:
When you can’t avoid giving me a difficult choice, you need to go out of your way to give me as much guidance as I need—but no more. Guidance should be brief, timely and unavoidable.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
CHAPTER:05
OMIT NEEDLESS WORDS
*KRUG’S THIRD LAW OF USABILITY*
Get rid of half the words on each page, then get rid of half of what’s left. (Removing half of the words without losing its value is actually a realistic goal). VIGOROUS WRITING IS CONCISE. (No unnecessary words, lines/parts) Demerits of not omitting needless words: page becomes daunting, its noise level increases, useful info diminishes)
*SOURCES OF NEEDLESS WORDS*
(a) HAPPY TALKS MUST DIE: Happy talk (ex: introductory text that’s supposed to welcome us to the site and tell us how great it is). It conveys no useful information (content-free) and it focuses on saying how great we are (for becoming sociable). Most Web users eliminate happy talks as much as possible. 
(b) INSTRUCTIONS MUST DIE: No one is going to read instructions—at least not until after repeated attempts at “muddling through” have failed. So, one should try to eliminate them (By making everything self-explanatory) or at least try to cut them back to bare minimum

Author: Explorin#4311
Content:
It's good considering your 1st iteration. However, I believe you have the potential to do a lot better with few more iterations. Please consider the following points for the next iteration:

Information Architecture:

1. Some information is needed for ensuring safety to the parents. 

2. You may try to rearrange the placement of time, location and date. It seems  The current version is not effortless in terms of consuming information. 

Visual Design:

1. Too many random illustrations...try to design with a minimalistic approach to have a elegant and effortless design. What you actually need is one relevant illustration placed appropriately.

2. Instead of illustrations, you use line icons for important details such as time, date and location. 

3. There is a lot to experiment with the background and typography. 

PS - The idea of a blue bg due to dress code is amazing. Your design thinking can be more amazing by trying different iterations. We expect atleast 5-7 iterations of this poster if you ever wish to explore design further. 

All the very best. Hope you had a great exploration experience 💚

Author: Senpai_JJ#8864
Content:
Hi. I went through your file. Let’s simplify the calculations because there are too many assumptions gone into file for deriving simple cashflows.

1) Things are good till post tax EBIT. But assumption that reinvestment deducted from this EBIT = FCFF is incorrect. Because not only it assumes high amount of CapEx without keeping into consideration financials, but also does not factor in depreciation, interest and working capital.

2) Derive FCFF using the standard process: EBIT (1-T) + Dep - WC - CapEx

3) Project Depreciation as a % of revenue.

4) Take the WC in terms of days. Calculate last 3 years Working Capital Days. Either take an average of three or keep the existing number of days and forecast it further. Derive the working capital value from revenues forecasted and assumed number of wc days.

5) CapEx figure can be forecasted by checking financials if they have made any CapEx historically or not. It’s not necessary that there would be investments made every year. So keep it constant I would suggest.

Author: Senpai_JJ#8864
Content: Lastly, the growth rate for terminal value assumed is too high. Nearly 5% terminal growth rate is higher than economy’s long term gdp growth estimates (2-3%). Reduce it and then I guess you should be able to achieve the right valuations.

Author: Senpai_JJ#8864
Content:
Reinvestment = any money that company has generated, invested back into business.

I’m not sure why would you say that CapEx - Depreciation + WC = reinvestment. Depreciation is a non cash expense.

Even if we assume for a minute that the logic of reinvestment is correct, then think about it this way. Is there actually that high amount of reinvestment needed for the company every year? Is there a need to have a higher working capital cycle and higher CapEx every year? Because there should be scaling benefits and over a period of time working capital cycle will reduce. The CapEx will be reduced to minimum maintenance CapEx because expansion of stores would be limited. Depreciation would reduce because asset value has been decreasing.

Author: Senpai_JJ#8864
Content:
Since your reinvestment is linked to Sales/ Capital ratio (which again I’m not very confident is the right method to use) -> You are thereby implying that every time there is growth in company, it is triggered due to higher reinvestment.

The logic is flawed because every business whenever infuses capital in the firm, takes a few years to achieve it’s peak efficiencies and highest utilisations, before it plans for further expansion. So the spike would only be for a few years.

Author: Senpai_JJ#8864
Content: I agree that using reinvestment as one standalone figure is easier to calculate rather than CapEx, Depreciation and Working Capital. But the idea is to understand and use a rational which is justified. We may not arrive at right answer even after forecasting these figures separately and that is okay, because you will be in a position to justify the assumptions taken into consideration.

Author: Keshav Bidawatka#6333
Content:
Hi comrades,
Are you giving away your attention to a lot of things resulting in overwhelm?

You alone aren’t the culprit here. Customer attention has become the most valuable currency for a digital product. All the companies are going all-out to gain some of your attention.

But this doesn’t mean that you give up. The control of your attention is your responsibility. It’s a currency that you own and you have the right to spend it towards your goals, dreams, and passion.

So, make it a habit to take a step back every day and observe where you are spending your attention throughout the day.

It looks really beautiful! Great work on visuals and monochromatic theme is nicely applied too. 😍 😍 The only thing that is disturbing me a bit is hierarchy of Kabir and celebrating is kept same which should not be ideally.

First iteration focuses on highlighting glossy texture of chocolate and red strawberries...main slide has gradient with two shades of choclate while the time-venue info is displayed in red wine color to draw ur attention towards strawberries. Different font styles (its cursive inspired by melting texture of chocolate) and font size are used to try to follow heirarchy for clear reading.
#2. The second iteration looks simple but it has deep sense. For instance, the alcoholic wine is sharing the screen with two stars.. these two stars are placed for following 2 reasons:
(a) two stars are overlapped to form a sign of electric charge (energy)
(b) these stars can be compared with two friends enjoying party just by hanging their shoulder around each other.
#3. The third iteration is displayed in a bit informative way with a tint of golden sparkles to reflect shine, color for nocturnal party vibes. I have also tried to give it a royal look by putting border element in rectangle at centre.
#4. This iteration has its all eye on funky font and blue balloons...the other info is shown on a shape which resembles the shape of balloon.

Author: mephisto#3939
Content:
hello!
I'm Akash and today I started my first personality goal. I read about Avoidance Coping (a coping mechanism which mainly includes avoidance or ignoring the situation).
The small videos and notes given me a whole new perspective of tackling a problematic situation. I learnt why we usually exhibits this type of behaviour and which is because we sometimes think that we can stop talking and keep avoiding the person or situation and that's going to make things slowly fine, but that doesn't happen. All it do is creating more misunderstanding and distances. There are more losses that one faces due to such behaviour such as indecisiveness, delays in works and emotional outbursts. This type of behaviour is not healthy for relationships, friendships.
The few techniques that one can use to overcome such issues is :
     Identify : Identify the situations that you've been avoiding recently. Sit down silently, focus on what you have done in past day or days which may have caused issue. Try to remember what you should've not done.
    Accept : Denial is always bad for personal growth as well as growth of relationship. All you have to do is accept. Go ask for forgiveness if you had a fight with a friend, or try to forgive that person and free you mind from constant restlessness.

Thanks for this great learning, I'll surely try to implement these techniques in my life to avoid personality losses.

Hey everyone,
I'm Lomsha. Today I completed my first goal of personal exploration. I understood about the importance of self talks on a person's life. What you feed to yourself is what you reflect. For this we need to IDENTIFY: negative aspects of self talks
ELIMINATE: replace the wrong feedings to right feedings 
SELF-SUFFICIENT: Believe you are enough for yourself.
SURROUND: Surround yourself with good people.
I will try to ensure that I am going ahead with these learnings.

Content:
Reading done!
1. Sharing a learning from the book I completed a couple of days before:
The book was about a dystopian futuristic society where emotions and individuality are conditioned out of children at a young age.
Hence, whenever somebody feels negative or upset emotionally, they take a medicine called 'soma" which cures the negative emotions and makes them happy.
This made me realize how lucky we are that we experience and live with both the negative and positive types of emotions. It's such a wonderful thing to persevere, endure and face emotional challenges. A journey of ups and downs is what makes us celebrate the wins🥳 .

From now, whenever you are not feeling or doing good, just remember whether it would be any good if you were deprived of that emotion forever. Just enjoy the mere existence of that emotion.

Author: anuj#7534
Content: I read about mindfulness and self mirror talk. So let's say, I have distraction problem that is claimed to be solved by practicing mindfulness(i.e. focusing on your breath and all) but what I think, it can also be solved by self mirror talk. Just telling yourself I love myself ,I am a focused man  to yourself will train your subconscious mind, so next time when your focus gets shifted your subconscious mind will order the conscious mind to return back to what has to be focused because you love yourself and no person will love himself by not focusing on things he wants to focus on. “If I love myself truly and deeply, would I let myself experience this?” The answer will  always be a “no” for someone who loves himself.

Author: chachacha#1243
Content:
Hey Radha, we are on the same page.
Completed my goals on mindfulness today.

 Well, I started my mindfulness journey exactly a year ago. I have been following Headspace and resonate with their ideas of mindfulness which were very similar to what I experienced in today's exercise.

Even though I have purchased the subscription to Headspace, my regularity takes a toll as we tend to get caught up in day to day thoughts a lot. Our restless thinking mind never stops creating stories.

 There are two things : thinking about mindfulness and meditation vs practicing mindfulness. When we start, we feel good and after some continuity many will fall into the trap of thinking about meditation. We need to moving out of the thinking and simply experience the present. 

I am at this stage right now.
Last year was a journey which was very irregular. But having experienced the vastness that comes with mindfulness, I aim to be more regular this year.

I have another important goal - reducing distraction. This is a big elephant in my mind that needs to tamed. Let's hope I get the power and tools to tame it. 💫

Author: Explorin#4311
Content:
Day 52 done

Failure and Success are two opposite sides of the same coin. Pain and Pleasure are just sensations as long as there is no filter of mind. As soon as mind, a limited filter, comes into picture...it's impossible to feel the ultimate truth. The concept of success exists because of the existence of 'failure'. 

Desires are of 2 types:
1. Noble
2. Material

Happiness accomplished through the completion of *noble desires* takes you in a state of ecstacy. However, chasing material desires ( status, power, money ) is equivalent to feeding the ego. When you let the *divine will* manifest inside you, which is only possible through destroying your ego...your every action turns into an act of selfless devotion. 

The world has no role to play. It's just a projection of physical reality on the screen of your mind. You are not what you see, you are what you feel. You don't create thoughts, you only receive them.

Author: mephisto#3939
Content:
hello!
I've completed the Assignments.
Applying learnings to a practical cause is really satisfying and mind opening. Although I have to say Pandas Profiling make a lot of task easier but still it's a job to get insights from those plot. EDA of stock price data and then predicting closing prices is a task which can be a gold mine if done accurately. I've learned to gain insights from the feature plotting. I got to know how one can find correlated features in a Data and finding outliers was also a cool task. I really liked the way we use the maths here. We've already studied Prob and Stats but actually using standard deviation and Z-score to find outliers in the data is very satisfying. 
I also learned scaling of Data although it wasn't in the learning but encountered it in a blog somewhere so thought of applying it in the task.
Linear Regression is somewhat of a complex linear algebra but applying it to make predictions of trends which vary linearly at some extent was very cool job I found.

Author: Mohit#8674
Content:
Ok so
A- Acquisition which means that how many of customers visit you website or your platform
A- Activation which means how many people took the first important step that is they gave you any sort of their information or anything that could be the first step towards contribution of your north star metric
R- Retention which means how frequently are they using your product or platform
R- Referral which means to how many other people they refer to your product which also means whether they are happy or not with your service
R- Revenue which means a customer finds your product enough valuable that they are willing to pay for your service

Other than these 5 I think their could be one more A which means awareness like how many know about your product or till how many persons you have reached till now?

These are my finding let me know your thoughts on it

Author: sparkling#3483

*LEARNING FROM MY GOAL#2* 
The video helps us to FIND A QUICKER WAY TO FIND OUR WHY’S? It suggests to start questioning what to oneself instead of why. We’ll end up getting solution to our problem. For instance, if I ask myself “WHY I eat so slowly?”; I might end up getting an emotional response from my brain, but instead, if I ask to myself that “WHAT makes me chew my food so slowly?”; I’ll get my solution!

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
Hello everyone! Today I started reading STEAL LIKE AN ARTIST book chapter-01 and came across some beautiful stuff...
#1. STEAL LIKE AN ARTIST.
    Artists fetch ideas by grabbing things that are worth stealing from surroundings!
    NOTHING IS ORIGINAL: …. “Everything that needs to be said has already been said. But, since no one was listening, everything must be said again.” BY Andre Gide.
    THE GENEALOGY OF IDEAS: We are the sum of our influences. German writer Goethe said, “We are shaped and fashioned by what we love.”
    GARBAGE IN, GARBAGE OUT: The artist is a collector who collects selectively what they really love. The more good ideas you collect, the more you can choose from to be influenced by. Steal what fuels your imagination. Select the only things that speaks to your soul. Do this and your work is authentic.
    CLIMB YOUR OWN FAMILY TREE: To build trust in artists, not art…Follow an action that read about one thinker you love. Then find out everything about people to whom thinker loved. Follow this to see yourself as part of a creative lineage will help you feel less alone as you start making your own stuff.
    SCHOOL YOURSELF: One should be curious about the world in which he lives. Chase down your reference after looking at things. Then, google everything. Don’t worry about doing research. Just search.
    SAVE YOUR THEFTS FOR LATER: Keep a swipe file with you to keep a track of things swiped from others. These swiped things should be worth stealing.

Author: Mohit#8674
Content:
Hello everyone from today I am gonna be regularly telling you guys about my learning of Product management

So topic that i am going to tell you about is The value proposition canvas.
It has two segment one is for product and other one is for customer.

Customer segment :- it has three sub part that is 

Customer Gains:- these are the outcomes that customer want to have or whatever has been expected from the product it has been upto expectation. It should be as concrete as possible.

Customer Pains:- these are the negative points which means that product has not been upto the expectations of the product or it is preventing customer from fulfilling its job. It should also be concrete as possible.

Customer Jobs:- it is something that customer wants to be completed it can be solving a problem or trying to perform any task.

Now coming to product segment it also has three sub parts 

Product and services:- it simply means what a product is all about or what is the service provided for each persona.

Gain creators:- it refers to how product create benefits to the user or outcome is satisfactory to the user.

Pain relievers:- it address the customers top pain points.

Let me know your thoughts upon it

Author: Mohit#8674
Content:
1. The VPC should have only these 2 components only that are product and customers because other than these two you as a product owner or developer is left and know one so your primary focus is  customer satisfaction and you will work upon your product as the customer demands and behave to the product.
2. It varies from person to person. It is true that whatever is a pain reliever for me can be  a gain creator of your. This is just to help the product manager in prioritising the  product in which one the team has to focus more.
3. No VPC is applicable to all the product and all kind of people taking the example of this community

Customer job :-  expecting from the community to gain experience of every field.

Customer Gains:- a student exploring a. Particular field come here and gain knowledge of other field as well and can clear his doubt as well.

Customer pains:-  it can be some student who want to explore any other field other than these 14 has to go somewhere else.
Possible that the resources provided are not good enough for someone.

Product :- building a community of students and mentors to give the knowledge and experience of every field they are interested to explore

Gain:- gives the knowledge and exposure to every field they wish to.

Pains:- can be mentors not supportive, resources are not satisfactory etc.

Author: Mohit#8674
Content:
In my previous learning, I told you about the value proposition Canvas, which is used for finding the opportunity for the product.

Now today I will be telling about KANO model of finding opportunities.
It has three principles that a product need to achieve to be successful over time:-
1. Value attracts customers.
2. Maintaining the quality, that builds loyalty.
3. Innovation to distinguish you from competitors.

Now mapping these principles:-

Basic Features:- These are the features that customers expect you to have. You cant get these features from surveys or interviews. For example, if your product doesn't have a password recovery option then it doesn't leave a positive impact on the user however if you have a very fast password recovery option then that doesn't mean that you leave a positive impact that means the level of unhappiness is decreased.

Performance Features:-These are the things customers are judging your product it is mainly the services you are providing. It also depends on how well you executed them. You can easily get these from an interview or a survey form. It could be the satisfier for the customer. For example, fast service leads to high satisfaction.

Excitement Features:- These are the features that is most difficult to find. You wont find it with customers interviews or surveys. These are the features that user dont know about. For example, getting WI-FI in midflight would be an wow experience. It will help you be above your competition.

Now as the time passes all the product lets take it aswifi in midflight for the first time it would be good but as soon as the time passes it shifts to performance features like if they get poor signal then that would be bad.

Let me know your opinion on this.

Author: argus#2468
Content:
Sure, the 5C framework abbreviation stands for Company, Customers, Collaborators, Competitors and Climate.
In most cases, these factors are useful in strategically understanding the company since it covers all the essential details.
Company: It refers to the company's experience, technology, culture, goals etc. Basically all questions related to the company.
Customers: The people/ market segment and their understanding.
Collaborators: External people/ dependencies (distributors, suppliers etc.)
Competitors: Understanding( strength, weaknesses etc.) the positioning of similar product by the competitors
Climate: The macro environmental factors like cultural, technological trends, innovations etc.

Author: anuj#7534
Content:
Seeing it from evolution point of view,
Our mind's are built against delayed gratification. In ancient times, when we were hunter gatherers, we were not even sure whether we will be alive tommorrow or not. So our primary aim was to maximize returns in short term. World evolved faster than our biological brain, today we are secure than than anytime ever before . We are still programmed to maximize returns in short term compromising huge long term gains. All sort of instant 
pleasures cigarette ,alcohol ,drugs, porn, gambling, calorie dense foods will give you pleasure in short term but the opportunity cost is very high. But this coginitive bias can be handled by acknowledging it consciously and programming our subconsious for all delayed gratification activities. Regularly doing physical activity ,control over fancy foods will give you a healthy body capable of doing miracles in long term and there are bunch of other examples. Personally I believe conquering all our cognitive biases will set us for 
immense success in any field ranging from health,wealth & relationships.

Hi everyone. I read a brilliant article on Mindsets. 
It might feel like a challenging read but do go through it.

Author: chachacha#1243
Content: https://tll.mit.edu/teaching-resources/inclusive-classroom/growth-mindset/z

Author: chachacha#1243
Content:
Mindsets are the implicit theories that individuals hold about the malleability of human characteristics. Research indicates that students’ beliefs about the nature of intelligence and ability significantly shape their response to academic challenges.
he mindset framework summarizes research on how people think, feel, and respond to failure and challenging experiences. Individuals who believe that intelligence and ability are largely immutable (‘fixed mindset’) respond to failure by withdrawing, disengaging, or persisting with the same set of strategies despite their prior demonstrated ineffectiveness.

On the other hand, students who believe they can substantially increase their intelligence and ability through experience and effort (‘growth mindset’) often react to academic challenges by allocating more effort, experimenting with new approaches, and seeking feedback. Students with a growth mindset set mastery goals and increasingly challenging tasks that promote skill development and acquisition.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
STEAL LIKE AN ARTIST
#2. *DON’T YOU KNOW ARE TO GET WAIT UNTIL WHO YOU STARTED.*
    IMPOSTER SYNDROME: We scare to start, which is quite natural. We should overcome this by just start making stuff via thinking that we’re ready!
    FAKE IT UNTIL YOU MAKE IT: Pretend to be something you’re not until you are or this can be done during making of something!
    START COPYING: Copying should not be misunderstood with plagiarism. Plagiarism is copying someone’s work and presenting it to others as your own. It is reverse engineering. We should know who to copy and what to copy. Who to copy is easier to know as it is basically what we love and what inspires us. What to copy is bit tricky since we don’t just steal the style, else we steal the thinking behind the style. The reason to copy your heroes and their style is so that you might somehow get a glimpse into their minds.
    IMITATION IS NOT FLATTERY: After sometime, imitation changes to emulation. Emulation is making your imitation as your own by making changes to it. Process to emulate is simple. One should copy, then find the where it falls short. It should be amplified by your own style which will make it yours! Merely imitating your heroes is not flattering them. Transforming their work into something of your own is how you flatter them.

Content:
Milestone 1
Goal 1: I see career dilemma as one of the most common issue amongst youth of my age, the major reason I find behind this is limited perspective due due to lack of exploration and guidance. From my point of view, the simple solution to the problem is to keep exploring under good mentorship until you until you find your passion
Goal 2: Choosing a path which is not a standard one is often discomforting due to the uncertainty in the path's direction. Furthermore the fear of getting away from the main stream is trembling. I believe following our passion, taking risks on the way in consideration could be a solution to the problem.
Goal 3: Settling too soon will probably lead to missing some opportunities followed by regret on the other hand it may also give you an early start, which could be beneficial provided that the path chosen is the right one.

Author: Deadman_PC#9610
Content:
Career
Personal Goal #1 - Career Dilemma
I was in a situation to decide what I should do. Then, I decided to go and try things by myself, but nothing seemed to provoke the curiousness in me and excite me until finally, case-solving did. Later, found out that consultants do similar stuff as a professional. The solution goes a lot in line with how it happened to me.
Personal Goal #2 - Road not Taken
It is a problem that arises due to a lack of self-belief as you are doing something which no one else is, and having someone to support you on that road when you have that fear of failure in your mind is undoubtedly a blessing. I think we should re-evaluate the path we are on to cure the problem of self-belief.
Personal Goal #3 - Let's Settle
Settling is something that takes you away from your life goals & makes you not push yourself to your max potential. It restricts your growth & hence, one should never settle no matter what. Once, you have identified your interest & goals, you know that you are going to achieve them. That is the required mindset. 
Settling gives you long-lasting regret & breaks down your confidence while by not settling you get a feeling of achievement, your confidence on the peak and you learn to be a warrior. Now, the choice is yours to settle or become a warrior.

Author: Axew#9456
Content:
Personality 

Goal 1 : I do not have to imagine this situation because I've been through one in my 10th standard, it was a small fight with Mr. X regarding some topic and I didn't try to fix things out. He was one of my best friends and I still regret spoiling a great friendship. So I would try not to do the same mistake again by making the first move.

Goal 2 : Automatic negative thoughts are very difficult to deal with, they also have various side-effects such as reduced productivity, fragile nature and anxiety. Solution to this problem can be achieved by meditation. Meditation helps you to analyze your thoughts and provides you a healthy and positive mindset. 

Goal 3: So now the problem is reacting to a situation under pressure. Impulsive behaviour and wrong decisions followed by regret are the outcome of such reactions. Keeping mind under control in such situations is the way to solve this problem, the simple way to do this is concentrating on your breath for a minute before you take a decision. Practicing vipassana in my knowledge is the best way to remain calm in even the worst situations, it helps us to control our mind and remain it in perfect equanimity or samata .

Author: Axew#9456
Content:
Milestone 3
Goal 1 : Misconceptions in professional life happen when there is lack of guidance, under confidence and/or lack of knowledge. One fails to judge their potential and a common question " Can I do it? " strikes repetitively. If this misconception persists then it may lead to a directionless path or working inefficiently. This problem can be resolved by proper interaction and guidance. Connecting to various people brings clarity to the issue. Spending time with like-minded people increases productivity and interest in the field.

Goal 2 : Lack of communication can happen in various situations, say when you want to keep something private or you don't want to interact at that moment. It becomes a problem when you're unable to communicate when you want to, the reason could be fear of judgement, lack of confidence or having preconceived notions. To solve the issue, you initially want to have a community with whom you feel comfortable, interacting with these people will boost your confidence, thereafter you should think from other's perspective in order to make the communication more efficient and meaningful.

Goal 3 : Being stuck in a situation feels powerless and suffocating. Many a times, being stuck causes hinderance in growth and may also cause mental stress. On the other hand, I feel getting in such circumstances provides an opportunity to come out stronger and be consummate than before. Now how to come out of it ….. reaching to people who are willing to provide a supporting hand, sharing your problems and vision with them will thereby yield positive outcomes. This process builds a better connect with your people and brings out a better form of you.

Content:
Career
career dilemma
This is the most common issue among my peers and the solution to this is proper guidance by someone who is an expert in a field and shear determination by one to get a sone knowledge in a particular field and then decide to continue it or not.

road not taken
Due to lack of time and other constraints people often give up their dreams and do something that doesn't give them satisfaction. The solution to this is that one should follow the path even if he is alone and should keep fighting even if they face failures.

let's settle
Too often I see people settling for things that are lower than their potential. In this case one should continuously evalute himself and if he/she is not happy about the decision they should talk to someone and get an advice what they should do to continuosly grow.

Author: RAJKUMAR#9295
Content:
Hello everyone, I achieved my  milestone by completing all 
three goals. I have learned the following points:
Goal 1: career dilemma
It's obvious that when we enter college life and see that many people are doing one thing let's say software development. so I will also start doing that thing no matter I am interested in that or not. it is because of a lack of guidance. So, if we do not have people around us, we can take help of some internet resources or some stuff related to that but we should not decide in a hurry without seeking proper guidance.
Goal 2: road not taken
It is a problem that arises due to a lack of self-belief as you are doing something which no one else is, and having someone to support you on that road when you have that fear of failure in your mind is undoubtedly a blessing. In these situations, we are generally afraid to be judged by other people. So, we should express ourselves properly, because when we express ourselves properly, and people listen to us there are major chances that they understand our point.
Goal 2:let’s settle
We should not settle for less but instead, fight for more. We should settle our goal and start fighting for that goal. There may be different paths but our goal should be fixed. Settling gives you long-lasting regret & breaks down your confidence while by not settling you get a feeling of achievement, your confidence on the peak and you learn to be a warrior. Now, the choice is yours to settle or become a warrior.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
STEAL LIKE AN ARTIST
#4. USE YOUR HANDS.
    STEP AWAY FROM THE SCREEN: In this digital age, computers have robbed the feeling us of the feeling that we’re actually making things. You can’t feel the things because they are immobile. ART THAT ONLY COMES FROM THE HEAD ISN’T ANY GOOD. The computer is really good for editing your ideas, and it’s really good for getting your ideas ready for publishing out into the world, but it’s not really good for generating ideas. Work station should have both types: analog as well as digital. Nothing electronic is allowed on analog desk. Once you start getting your ideas, then you can move over to your digital station and use the computer to help you execute and publish them. When you start to lose steam, head back to the analog station and play.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
STEAL LIKE AN ARTIST
#6. THE DO-GOOD SHARE IT SECRET: WORK AND WITH PEOPLE.  
    IN THE BEGINNING, OBSCURITY IS GOOD: When in the beginning, when there is no captive audience, you can do what you want. There’s no pressure! This freedom can work wonders for you…just use it when no one is noticing you because once everyone is paying attention to you, you’ll never get this freedom. ENJOY YOUR OBSCURITY WHILE IT LASTS. USE IT.
    THE NOT-SO-SECRET FORMULA: For becoming known, there’s no such formula. JUST DO GOOD WORK AND SHARE IT WITH PEOPLE (on internet). STEP1: Wonder at something. STEP2: Invite others to wonder with you. When you open up your process and invite people in, you learn. If you don’t want to share your complete idea, then SHARE YOUR DOTS, BUT DON’T CONNECT THEM.

Author: notsosuresudhanshu#2270
Content:
Hey everyone, it's what I understood and recollected by completing my Milestones.
Goal 1: Career Dilemma
I think we often find ourselves in a dilemma where we don't ask the right questions to ourselves. We are too afraid to ask them. We focus on the short-term benefits rather than looking it at a bird view.
Goal 2: Road not taken
Most of us do not try the road not taken and even if we try and explore there is information in abundance where we focus on the pros and not balancing it out with the conc. Its's all well and good untill it's time we face the conc.
Good 3: Let's Settle
When we choose to explore there comes a lot of bad days where you don't feel like continuing but there are some good days which keeps you motivated through out the journey. The way we react to the bad days is what defines us. "Fear makes us procrastinate more than laziness ever will".

Author: Mohit#8674
Content:
Customer development

Generally there are two times when a customer interview usually takes place, the former happens at the beginning of the product process, and the later will happen once we’ve started building something.
In the beginning the goal the main purpose of survey or interview is to figure out whether to build a given thing or not rather than t to conduct user testing/research to see if we’ve built a particular thing well

It’s a way to validate if the people you think are your customers truly are the right customers and confirming you’re on the right path. Fundamentally, it’s a conversation and an exchange of information. 

Customer development is not a way for people to give you a wish list. It’s not a focus group to only see how people respond to ideas. It’s not a place to observe how customers use your prototype. It’s also not a replacement for product vision. Customers will give you a huge wish list, but they’ll often ask for more than they actually need, end up not using features

Interviews

Interviewing is an incredibly valuable skill because it’s an effective and low-cost way to validate your opportunity hypothesis. 
Just like how you don’t walk into a job interview without preparing, or a meeting without anticipating a desired outcome, customer interviews take preparation.

Some points you should note down before taking any customer interview:-
Write down a list of what you know factually 
What you’re assuming about our customers, including their needs
How your product satisfies them

Some models that can help you get your questions answered are as follows:-

Business Model Canvas can help you identify key assumptions. Of course, customers can help you validate only parts of the canvas that apply to them
Value Proposition Canvas to identify what you know for sure and what you’re assuming are your customers’ existing pains and desired gains

Author: Mohit#8674
Content:
A very good way of writing your hypothesis is as follow:- 

I believe that <personas/segments> experience <this pain> when doing <task> because of <limitation> , and alleviating that pain would let the customer <achieve this gain> , although she’d have to <accept these limitations>.
Some points to remember the screener questions  of the right customers are as follows :-

Try to hide the “right” answer so that people don’t answer with what they think you want to hear. 
The most important thing to know is that, whether they realise it or not, people are going to try to please you.
It’s also really valuable when you ask questions that get customers to tell you stories rather than giving simple yes/no answers.


Rather than asking customers if they’d like your feature/product— because they’ll say yes—it’s better to find out about how they deal with the fundamental problem you’re trying to solve. The simplest way to ask a question like this is, “Tell me about how you do <topic> today.”
