Author: utkarsh#1616
Content:
#data-and-analytics 
**Doubt regarding data fetching in DS_3 Goal 1.**

It says you have to fetch the data of top 100 companies according to market capitalization. 

Steps to do that: 
**step 1** Refer to tbe library i.e. nsepy which gives you the open, close, high low price,etc of any given company.  The catch is you have to pass the symbol of that company and the duration between which you want the data.


**step 2** Search for a excel file which consists the name and symbol of top 100 companies, you will get it on internet. 


**step 3** Define a function which loop through the symbol column of the excel file.


**step 4** Take one of the column of each company, for ex close price and construct the dataframe having dates in row and column as close price of 100 companies.  


**step 5** Attach last column for sensex data. And hurray your dataset is ready for next process.


If you are still stuck somewhere please let me know. 

Happy exploring 🎉

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Read more about volatility from a book : 
Volatility
1-Expected volatility
2- Implied volatility
3- historical volatility
HV : 
HV is a measure of how volatile the price movement of a security has been
during a certain period of time.
Expressed in terms of standard deviations.
IV : 
IV is a measure of how volatile the stock will be in future.
IV depends on supply and demand in market.
HV-IV Divergence
An HV-IV divergence occurs when HV declines and IV rises or vice versa.
Expected stock volatility:
Yearly standard deviations can be related to that

 of one day or one week by dividing the standard

 deviations for 1 year by sqrt of number of

 trading days that year to calculate for one day

 and multiply number of trading days sqrt to

 calculate for 1 month.

Technical analysis:
Technical analysis is the study of market data, such as past prices or volume,
which is manipulated in such a way that it better illustrates market activity.
Fundamental analysis:
Fundamental analysis is the study of economic factors that affect the
value of an asset in order to determine what it is worth.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
Good Morning Dreamers 💙

Yesterday, My day at the office was amazing ✨

After my First project review, I had shifted to the Index Trading Desk, where almost everyone was 15-20 Years of Experience in Market

So My desk was in between my manager and senior trader, Aftermarket closed at around 4 PM no one was there except my manager on that floor
I was noting the IVs of EOD for Nifty and Bank Nifty, Then my manager, I mean he is also a senior trader who was a pioneer in Skew Trading, came to me and reviewed my progress
Then I started to ask questions to him, He was explaining each and every minute detail with practical examples
I was wondering that the discussion went for 2.5 Hrs, Literally 2.5 Hrs a manager spending time with an Intern just to Ignite me with his knowledge was amazing 💙
Post that he discussed
- The scope of trading, 
- How a typical trading firm functions 💲
- What's the growth curve of a trader 🌠
- A day in a Life of a Trader 👨‍💻
- Strategies they are using (Typically they use only 5 Strategies with 5 different cases for each strategy): Key Learning we can take is, We don't need complex models to make money in markets, all we need is simple strategies with consistent performance and especially emotional control 
- How to be stable in every situation and emotional controlling 🙌 e.t.c

Technical learnings for the day: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1r0ONjik3MiePLZ5-OdWd1-XwAEiZfpW2kCNtzHGjCwY/edit?usp=sharing

Content:
Anger is caused when things not goes according to our plan , when you are not able to express yourself or might be anyone is not able to get you.
As you mentioned meditation and all... keep in mind they won't work like your code in vs code that you just need to press run button it takes time.
If you want short term relief from anger just be with the community you love to be with or talk to those who really care for you and want to really know what you are feeling inspite or just listening and ignoring.
For long term solution you need to realise that always things won't go the way you have planned, life can't be always fair and perfect life is just an assumption.
Hope it helps!!❤️

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning:- 
Option greeks
Factor that impact option price
1- Type of option
2- Underlying price
3-Time to expiration
4- Strike price
5- Volatility
6- Interest rate
7- Dividend (if paid)
Important points
* Long call and short put will benefit when underlying price rises and vice-versa
* Short call and long put will benefit when underlying price fall and vice-versa
* Increase in underlying price benefit call option buyer and decrease in same benefits holder of put option
* Moneyness= strike price- underlying price
* Strike price is below underlying price for call option it is ITM
* Higher time to expiration higher will be probability of option moving in favour of buyer
* Rise in interest rate benefits value of call and hurt put option
* Delta is probability of option expiring in the money
* Higher delta means high risk
*ITM  delta is inversely proportional to volatility.opposite for OTM
* Gamma measure change in directional risk
* Gamma will be high when strike price-stock price at T will be 0.
* Person buys option,gamma is positive
* Person sell option,gamma is negative
* Buyer of both call and put will benefit when IV go up and lose when IV go down.
* Vega is positive for long and negative for short option
* Vega is identical for both put and call
* Vega impacts only time value not intrinsic value
* Higher the time to expiration,higher would be vega or equal
* Vega highest for ATM 
* When moving towards ITM or OTM vega declines.

Author: anuj#7534
Content:
Read about cognitive ease from thinking fast and slow and here is what I learned. 

Human thinking is flawed, we have hundreds of biases in our judgments. We will believe/trust something very easily without enquiring which is easy to understand, depicted through cool visuals, or through common words which are easy to comprehend and are repeated in day to day life, said when we were  in a good mood by a person whom we like or trust. The thing is *Hitler was born in 1889* is not true just because I wrote it in italics or you were in a good mood when you read it or it was said by your crush xd.

Author: anuj#7534
Content: So what should we do?  We can't go and check everything whether it's false, we are limited by our time and energy and therefore can't invest it everywhere. I have made a rule for myself, when important things are at stake( so now the question comes what things are important? Decisions that will affect you coming months or years i.e. considerable part of your life can be considered important), I will not let these biases disbelieve the truth,just because it was said by someone who I like or I was in a good mood or is being repeated in my daily life.

Author: anuj#7534
Content: P.S. Hitler was actually born in 1889 xd, check it out on google

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Things I learnt today
Delta 
* How moneyness impact it
* How time impacts it
* How volatility impacts it
* Delta is rate of change in price of an option for every 1 point move in price of underlying.
* Delta of call option is (0-1).
* Delta of put option is (-1,0).
* New option price = Old option price + Delta*(new underlying price - old underlying price).
* Delta represent the probability of option expiring ITM.
* ITM call delta ranges from 0.5 to 1 .
* ATM call delta is 0.5 .
* OTM call delta ranges from 0 to 0.5 .
* ITM put delta ranges from -0.5 to -1 .
* ATM put delta is -0.5  .
* OTM put delta ranges from -1 to -0.5 .
* Delta of underlying is 1.
* Option having higher delta are more responsive to change in price of underlying.
* For ITM ,delta of an option closer to expiry is higher and vice-versa.
* For OTM ,delta of an option closer to expiry is lower and vice-versa.
* For ATM ,delta of an option closer to expiry is lower and vice-versa.
* For ITM ,delta of an option higher if low volatility and vice-versa.
* For OTM ,delta of an option higher means high volatility.
* Value of delta keeps changing as other variables do 
* Important : call delta + put delta = 1.

Content:
Hello everyone, I have completed my Goal 4 in Data science. It was very challenging for me as well as very informative and knowledgeable...

Here are my learnings...

1. I learned about decision trees and how to make predictions using these trees, I found it very useful if you know how to ask optimal questions to classify things.
2. I also learned about ensembling methods.. and It shows how from many small decision trees or models we can create our own ensembled model with better predictions. It is the thing that takes most of my time in the goal but at the same time returns the most too.
3. Then I learned different types of ensembling models made on decision trees like AdaBoost, LightGBM, XGBoost, CatBoost, and GradientBoost. 

After learning this stuff when I faced the real-world scenario given in the problem statement, first I was not able to get how I will use these things in the problem... eventually reading notebooks and getting the idea make things more clear to me and finally I did what is needed in the problem. Overall it was a nice experience for me to work on this problem and I learned much from this.

Thanks to @utkarsh for helping me out in many places..

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning
Gamma
* How it impacts delta, how moneyness impact it.
* How time to expiration and volatility impacts it.
* Gamma is rate of change of delta for every 1 point move in price of underlying.
* Delta measures directional risk and gamma measure change in directional risk.
* Rising gamma mean any change in price of underlying would be greater change in delta, which leads to greater change in option price.
* At ATM gamma is highest. When move towards ITM or OTM gamma reduces.
* Deep ITM or OTM gamma is 0.
* Gamma for buyer is positive while for seller is negative.
* Gamma causes delta of long option to move 0 when call option underlying price decrease or rises for put
* Seller wants underlying to be stable.  *Gamma variation with time to expiration
                  
ITM.                        Short time.          Higher
                                Long time.          Lower
ATM to OTM.        Short time.           Higher
                                Long time.         Lower
ATM.                       Short time           Increase
                               Long time.         Decrease

* Gamma of ITM or OTM reduce when time to expiration is near.
* Deep ITM or OTM gamma falls for short time to expire and vice-versa.
* Gamma of ATM increase as time in expiration near.
* Gamma high for ATM with low volatility and it starts reducing as volatility increase.
* As volatility increase, gamma of ITM and OTM reduce.
* When deep OTM or ITM , increase in volatility cause gamma to be higher.
* Gamma curve tends to be sensitive to price change in low volatility than to price change in high volatility.
* Signs of delta and gamma 
                            Delta.                    Gamma
Long call.          Positive.               Positive
Short call.          Negative.             Negative
Long put.           Negative.            Positive
Short put.           Positive.              Negative

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of what I learnt today
Theta
* Theta measure impact of time on price of option.
* Theta is defined as change in option price for a one unit change in time left to expiration.
* Theta is defined as lost of option value as a result of time decay.
* Time decay is the rate at which the value of an option erodes with each passing day.
* Theta works in favour of option writer and against option buyer
* Theta is negative for long position and positive for short position.
* Price of an option reduces each day by theta.
* Call value erode slightly Higher than put.
* ATM 
* has highest theta
* Theta increase in absolute value with passing days , before starting to rise exponentially as expiration gets closer.
* ATM is risky because of rapid declining theta will rapidly erode time value of option.
* ITM
* Intrinsic value form larger component
* Have low theta , deep ITM have low loss in terms of time value.
* Theta tends to increase at slower rate, before starting to fall sharply as expiry gets closer 
* OTM 
* Have only time value no intrinsic value
* Deep OTM , lower time value lower theta
* Theta increase at slower rate before exponential decrease
* Higher volatility, higher time value of an option , higher option value.
* Fall in time value of option with high volatility tends to be greater than fall in time value option with low volatility.
* Low volatility, fall in time value is steadier.

Frankly, I am looking for reasons to wake up everyday. There's not much I do everyday but here I am to change the way I live. I am looking forward to make friends with you all.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Revised volatility and read about vega
* Volatility is rate at which price of an asset fluctuate over time.
* Historical volatility measures the dispersion around mean for daily returns on an Annualised basis.
* Implied volatility is measure of future volatility.
* Vega is defined as change in option price for every 1% change in implied volatility.
* Higher the IV higher would be change in option price.
* Buyer of a call or put benefit when IV go up.
* Seller of a call or put benefit when IV go down.
* Vega is positive for long position and negative for short position.
* Long means you have long vega exposure and short means you have short vega exposure.
* Rising volatility works against option seller.
* Vega is identical for all call and put.
* Vega impacts only time value component of option price that is extrinsic value not the Intrinsic value.
* Higher time to expiration, higher would be vega
* Vega is highest for ATM.
* As moving either ITM or OTM vega starts declining
* Vega is too low for deep ITM and OTM.
* Maximum impact of change in IV tends to occur for options that are ATM because they tend to have highest vega.
* Closer the probability of option expiring ITM moves towards extreme lower will be vega

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning
Black scholes model
* It is differential equation widely used to price option contract.
* It requires 5 input variables, strike price of an option, current stock price, Time to expiration, risk free rate and volatility.
* Due to certain assumptions price deviate from real world results.
* Only used in European option as it doesn't take into account that American option can be exercised before time to expiration.
* BSM posits that instrument, such as stock shares or future contact, will have lognormal distribution of prices following a random walk with constant drift and Volatility.
* It is theoretically possible for option seller to set rational prices for the option that they are selling.
* Model predicts that the price of heavily traded asset follow a geometric browninan motion with constant Volatility and drift.
Assumptions :- 
* No dividend are paid out during the life of an option.
* Markets are random
* There are no transactions costs in buying an option.
* Risk free rate and volatility of the underlying asset are known and constant
* Returns on the underlying asset are log- normally distributed
* Option is European and can be only exercise at expiration.
Volatility skew :- 
* BSM assume stock price follow lognormal distribution because asset prices cannot be negative.
* Asset prices are observed to have significant right skewness and some degree of kutosis. This means high risk Downward moves often happens in market than normal distribution.
Drawback :-
* Used for only European call and do not consider American option can be exercised before expiration.
* Assume dividend and risk free rate are constant, but this may not be true in reality.
* Model also assume volatility remain constant over option life.

Content:
@everyone 
Have you heard of **DALL-E 2** ?
Its a new creation from AI research group ***OpenAI(co-founded by Elon Musk)***
**A text to image generation program** that can create realistic images and art from a description in natural language.
> DALL·E 2 can create original, realistic images and art from a
> text description. It can combine concepts, attributes, and styles.

> It can make realistic edits to existing images from a natural language caption. It can add and remove elements while taking shadows, reflections, and textures into account.

> It can take an image and create different
> variations of it inspired by the original.

`It has learned the relationship between images and the text used to describe them. It uses a process called “diffusion,” which starts with a pattern of random dots and gradually alters that pattern towards an image when it recognizes specific aspects of that image.`

> The dog image was generated from the description “A Shiba Inu dog wearing a beret and black turtleneck”

Seems interesting ? 
The demo video is worth to watch

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning
Mutual fund
* Type of investment consisting of portfolios of stocks, bonds or other securities.
* It give small or individual investors access to diversified, professionally managed portfolios at low price.
* Mutual fund are divided into several categories representing kind of securities they invest in, their investment objective and type of return they seek.
* Mutual funds charge annual fees or commission in some cases, which affect their overall return.
* Overwhelming majority of money in employer sponsored retirement plan goes into mutual funds.
* Value of mutual fund company depends on performance of security it decides to buy.
* Unlike stock, mutual fund shares do not give its holders any voting rights.
* Voting rights :- right of a shareholder to vote on matters of corporate policy, issuing new securities.
* Net Asset value :- represent the net value of an equity and is calculated as total value of entity's assets minus total value of liabilities.
* How investors earns return
* From dividend
* If fund sells securities that have increased in price, capital gain.
* If fund holding increase in price but are not sold by fund manager, fund's share increase in price.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Revision notes
Delta :- 
* Delta is rate of change in price of an option for every 1 point move in price of underlying.
* Call option : (0,1) Put option : (-1,0)
* Delta represent the probability of an option expiring in ITM
* Call ITM : 0.5-1    ATM : 0.5      OTM : 0 to 0.5
* Put ITM : (-0.5,-1).  ATM : -0.5.   OTM : 0 to -0.5
* Delta of underlying is 1
* For OTM , delta of option close to expiry are lower 
*  For ITM , delta of option close to expiry are higher
* For ATM , delta of option close to expiry are lower
* For OTM and ITM delta lower if underlying has  low and high volatility respectively.
* Call delta + put delta = 1
* Delta measures directional risk
* Gamma 
* Gamma is rate of change of delta for every 1 point move in underlying price
* Gamma is highest for ATM
* When move towards ITM or OTM gamma reduces
* Deep ITM or deep OTM gamma is 0.
* Buyer : gamma (+ve), seller : gamma (-ve)
* ITM , short time to expiration, gamma higher than long time
* ATM - OTM , short time , gamma higher than long time
* ATM , short time , gamma higher than long time
* Gamma is high for ATM with low volatility and it starts reducing as volatility increase
* With increasing volatility gamma of ITM and OTM reduce
* For ITM or OTM, as time to expiration reduce gamma reduces
* Theta
* Change in option price for a one unit change in time left to expiration
* Theta works in favour of option seller and against buyers
* Negative for long call and long put
* Call value erode slightly Higher rate than put.
* ATM has highest theta
* ITM, intrinsic value form larger component of option price
* OTM have only time value
* Higher the volatility, higher will be theta

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
* Vega
* Change in option price for a one percent change in IV
* Vega is positive for long position
* Long means having long vega exposure
* Vega is identical for call and put
* Vega impacts only time value component of option price
* Higher time to expiration, higher would be vega
* Vega highest for ATM
* Maximum impact of change in IV tends to occur for options that are ATM because they tend to have highest vega

Author: utkarsh#1616
Content:
Hey @everyone 
Back with another AI Creation.
How would you feel if you just pass question to the machine and it will **code for you**?
**So what does this mean for programming? Does it mean that there is no point in learning programming because it will get fully automated?**

We don't believe so. Here is what we think the impact will be:

> We'll have tools that help us code faster. We'll see more sophisticated code generation and refactor tools, and repetitive coding tasks -- the moments you see yourself copy-pasting code -- might get automated away wholly.
> 
> AI will make it easier to learn programming (and many other things). Imagine Codecademy-like courses entirely guided by AI with conversational abilities.
> 
> Eventually, AI will influence how we design programming languages, and a new class of languages will emerge. Since computers will be better and faster than humans at generating code, the act of programming itself might change. Who knows, we might be able to program by talking or even by moving in VR/AR.

At some point -- probably not in the near future -- `the word "coding" will disappear `from our lexicon because programming will stop requiring code and instead be about the pure act of solving problems using computers making it accessible to more and more people.

In the meantime, if you haven't yet, you should still learn how to code and get good at it. It's unlikely that things will change meaningfully in the short-term, and coding is still the best way to program computers. But keep your eyes open to the future, as many AI groups like Repl.it is building the most advanced programming environment regardless of the modality.

Read more about how can you code simply using AI or understand using AI https://blog.replit.com/codingai

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summing up today's learning
Types of mutual funds
* Equity fund :- this sort of fund invests principally in stocks. Within this group are various subcategories.
* Fixed income fund :- focuses on investments that pay a set rate of return, such as government bonds, corporate bonds, or other debt instruments
* Index fund :- investment strategy is based on the belief that it is very hard, and often expensive, to try to beat the market consistently.
* Balanced fund :- Balanced funds invest in a hybrid of asset classes, whether stocks, bonds, money market instruments, or alternative investments. The objective is to reduce the risk of exposure across asset classes.
* Money market fund :- consists of safe , short-term debt instruments, mostly government treasury bills.
* Income funds :- These funds invest primarily in government and high-quality corporate debt, holding these bonds until maturity in order to provide interest streams.
* International funds :- invests only in assets located outside your home country.
* Speciality fund :- consists of funds that have proved to be popular but don't necessarily belong to the more rigid categories.
* Regional fund :- make it easier to focus on a specific geographic area of the world.
* Socially responsible fund :- invest only in companies that meet the criteria of certain guidelines or beliefs.
* Exchange traded fund :- they are structured as investment trusts that are traded on stock exchanges and have the added benefits of the features of stocks.

Content:

Author: Keshav Bidawatka#6333
Content:
https://www.myhatchpad.com/insight/how-to-excel-as-a-product-manager-at-an-early-stage-startup/

Found this blog very interesting. I strongly suggest those interested in being PMs at early-stage startups to give it 2 minutes. @anuj @Mohit @sourabkumar004 @Khush @vedant11 @argus @Aman Vishwakarma 

Two learnings stood out for me:
1. The thing that product people often fail to appreciate is how hard it is to go from an idea to having even a couple hundred thousand dollars of revenue. It’s a skillset that product people rarely have themselves.
That empathy ultimately enables you to have conversations with the founders around pivoting and adapting existing product strategies to help prepare for the next stage of growth and make the company successful. But that level of respect and understanding must always be brought with you; otherwise, you’re just going to set yourself up to fail.

2. **An often-overlooked aspect of early-stage product management is that different PMs come in and add value at certain stages:**

**You want to have the openness to serve for as long as you’re useful and recognize that there’s nothing wrong with moving on to the next thing and passing the baton to someone else to take the company to the next level.**

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
I have started reading "Identity Designed is a good one". Here's the introduction:
*INTRODUCTION*
The idea is a result of careful observation, and the design is a product of that idea. -PAUL RAND
A VISUAL IDENTITY is to business what faces are to people. 
SYMBOLISM represents what people think of a certain brand’s identity. For instance, bitten apple represents apple brand. A brand’s identity includes logo, website, vehicle graphics and many more, while in broader identity we incorporate signage, carrier bags, typefaces, language, etc. 
GOOD DESIGNS do not need to be complicated. Only the necessary stuff on the table works as strongest design. In this competitive world, potential customer and even every customer compares the packaged ways to judge its quality. How a product looks must reflect the quality of what’s on scale.
CONSISTENCY IS OFTEN WRONGLY ASSOCIATED WITH SAMENESS, BUT IT CAN MEAN CONSISTENTLY DISTINCTIVE AND VIBRANT. If consistency is used correctly, it can turn potential buyers into loyal customers and advocates.
DESIGN HAS TO WORK, ART DOES NOT. -Donald Judd.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
Chapter01 is about LANTERNS in case studies:
*CASE STUDIES*
1.    LANTERN:
Project: Primary Roots
FIRST MEET or call with clients includes conversation related to understanding business, their ambitions for the projects and the key deliverables. We show them our credibility by showing some nicely Photoshopped projects. A lot of what we do is based upon the messaging and the attitude, character, and personality of the brand.
THE VERBAL SIDE OF BRAND: The name “Nature’s Gym” was changed to “Primal Roots” because former is functional, while later is emotional.
DESIGN PRICING: As one grows in credibility and awareness, increment in rates is crucial. If a client ever wants the price reduced, try to reduce what you deliver instead. Try not to begin the creative work until a down payment has been made. Payments should be transferred using bank transfer (using for instance PayPal). You can stipulate an interest rate for late payment.
AUDIT, WORKDHOPS AND BRIEF: After receiving down payment, audit the client’s brand to know what they’re about, what their sector’s about, who their competitors are, and how they’re marketed. Once the audit is done, workshops are held, not only with the people involved in the business, but also with the beneficiaries (for instance, we can discuss about best-practice brands in similar sector). Challenges of projects are “pain points”, we should discuss these with clients as how we can turn a potential negative into a positive that people will embrace. Following our audits and workshops, we put together the creative brief that the client needs to agree upon. The brief is essentially the structural framework to make sure that nothing goes wrong in the creative interpretation that we share. Instead of creating 4/5/6 options (among them only 2 are really good), we’d rather spend more time crafting those two options than delivering six options.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
A STARTEGIC APPROACH: The amount of strategy depends on the job (proportion of design to strategy varies from project to project). Capturing the attitude and spirit of the business is always a great jumping off point for the messaging to develop. Its good to focus on the verbal first and then blend it with the visual as the project develops. Brand manifesto is not necessarily the external face, it can be emotional position that reflects the brand identity.
ON FINDING IDEAS: Sometimes thinking over something continuously can become frustrating. Have a break as it will crystallise an idea or maybe distill things a little more! Design is about having that built-in ability to understand when something feels like it’s an appropriate fit. Functional side is about briefing it. 
DESIGN PRESENTATION: With a start with brief of outtakes from the workshops, you can lead them through number of creative routes you made. After that, it’s easy to turn a room to think in one direction when you’re the first person to speak. But don’t push them in your direction, let client speak first since they know the brand better than anyone. If they choose one, feedbacks are listened and refinements are done. If they ask for a new route, it means that brief went wrong. 
DEVELOPING GUIDELINES: Guidelines are set for two reasons: Consistency (showing core toolkit/fixed elements that include typography, logo, colours, etc) and Creativity (how to use these elements). Guidelines are’nt rules, they should allow creativity. 
STUDIO MARKETING: The more people you surround yourself with, the greater the chance that one of those people will know someone who needs design or branding work.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning
* Put-call parity shows the relationship between European put and call options that have the same underlying asset, expiration, and strike prices.
* Put-call parity doesn't apply to American options.
* If the put-call parity is violated, then arbitrage opportunities arise.
* Put-call parity states that simultaneously holding a short European put and long European call of the same class will deliver the same return as holding one forward contract on the same underlying asset, with the same expiration, and a forward price equal to the option's strike price.
* If the prices of the put and call options diverge so that this relationship does not hold, an arbitrage opportunity exists. 
* Protective put :- If the prices of the put and call options diverge so that this relationship does not hold, an arbitrage opportunity exists. 
* fiduciary call is a long call combined with cash equal to the present value of the strike price . This ensures that the investor has enough cash to exercise the option on the expiration date.
* An option's price is the sum of its intrinsic value, which is the difference between the current price of the underlying asset and the option's strike price, and time value, which is directly related to the time left until that option's expiry.
* But now a days BSM is used to determine the option price.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
Greetings to all! Here's some crucial practical learnings, I absorbed from Chapter02 **BASE**
Project: Ruhrtriennale (Music, dance, theater, performance, and fine arts in the former industrial buildings of the Ruhr Area—that’s the Ruhrtriennale)
RULES OF CLIENT ACQUISITION: Don’t accept a job if you don’t have access to a decision maker. 
PROJECT DELIVERABLES: Task was to create the Ruhrtriennale global concept and identity, including poster templates and digital and print guidelines.
HOW WE PRICE: Generally, they price their work by gathering the designers, writers and strategists to evaluate how much time each phase would take. Budget (decided by scope of work and expectations) serves the framework. 
NEGOTIATING: Successful negotiation was addressing the needs of the client while retaining our excitement for the task.
THE CONTRACT: A good contract is not only linked to money. It’s an agreement between two people or two companies that also covers the deliverables, the time frame, and the methodology, including the people assigned to the project. It’s key to get a signed contract before starting.
UNDERSTANDING THE CLIENT: You can provide tools and ideas to help them, but it’s their brand, not yours. 
CONDUCTING RESEARCH: Its crucial that everyone learns from everyone else. So, its better to have an open discussion between researchers, strategy makers and designers. During research, they visited various venues around the Ruhr region. It was a culturally diverse region with people from different countries. So, they needed to embrace a whole region through opera, theatre and contemporary dance. It was quite ambitious.
THE ROLE OF STRATEGIST: It is vital to frame and give voice to your creative work. Words are extremely important in our design process at Base. 
THE IDEA: The idea for this project was that it wasn’t necessarily formed by thinking of music, it could be something crazy or something of interest. Content was the driving force.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
WHEN TO STOP EXPERIMENTING: You decide when the work is finished. At some point, leader summarize things: “This is probably the way to go, do you agree? Is this what we want to proceed with?” Everyone needs to be in agreement, and if someone in the room doesn’t like the direction for a specific reason, we need to do more research.
HONESTY: When you can say to the person working next to you that you don’t like or understand what they created or that it needs more work, you’ve reached a level of honesty that’s key. Let the team members be their own team leaders. They commit to what they create and they’re in charge of what they produce. Team spirit: Our team wants to help those who aren’t doing so well.
PRESENTING IDEAS: in. In that initial presentation, they communicate the strategy, integrated with words and design. 
TRADEMARKING AND GUIDELINES: Trademarking a logo is a work of lawyer. Guidelines are designed by them using a toolbox. It includes the basic tools used to identify a brand: not only the graphics, but the wording, tone of voice, social media communication, and every dimension, but in a very simple way, creating a simple tool that’s easy to use. Nobody wants to read a 100-page manual.
MEASURING SUCCESS: Success of any project is not solely based on external communication instead, it’s also internal, helping the client to be more unified behind a vision and direction. 
ADVICE FOR WORKING WITH CLIENTS: First, it comes down to the quality of how you listen. Second, dare to challenge the various processes if they don’t suit you. One should build relationships in order to understand their clients. The key to any good job is a good human relationship. Third, be demanding of yourself and the client. Fourth, think about how to prompt, “Oh, I didn’t expect that, wow.”

Author: Keshav Bidawatka#6333
Content:
Let's take an example of day planning.
I am currently struggling to measure my progress in my ability to plan my day.
So, I have started with a process of 
1. Write down my short-term and long-term goals.(This process ensures that I am planning my day due to a purpose)
2. Write down the activities I have to do to achieve those goals and prioritise them ( This process forces me to think of actions that would help me achieve my goals)
3. Use Eisenhower Matrix to decide to-do tasks for today(The process to plan today)
4. Analyse weekly whether my activities are taking me towards my purpose(This process forces me to measure my progress towards my purpose)

Then I again jump to the first process and these progress continue in a loop to improve my ability of day planning.

Does this make sense?

Author: Keshav Bidawatka#6333
Content:
The first two steps of this process has been inspired by what I learnt from @jai2201 today:

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning
Bull call spread :- 
* Spread are multi leg strategies involving 2 or more options.
* Bull call is best when outlook for stock is moderate, could be moderately bullish or bearish
* Spread strategies
 1- protects from downside cases
2 - amount of profit that we will make is also predictable
 3- As a trade off, get to participate in market for lesser cost.
* Comes in hand when we have moderately bullish view on stock.
* To implement bull call spread  
 1- buy one ATM call option
 2- Sell one OTM call option
* What to ensure
 1- Stocks belong to same underlying
 2- Belong to same expiry series
 3- each leg involve same number of options
* When spot price is less than both options strike price and when spot price is less than OTM strike but equal to ATM strike price then loss happens but is limited to a certain value
*  When spot price is greater than both options strike price and when spot price is greater than ATM strike but equal to OTM strike price then profit happens but is limited to a certain value.
* Spread = difference of higher and lower strike price.
* Bull call max spread loss = net debit of strategy
* Net debit = premium paid- premium recieved
* Bull call maximum profit = spread - net debit.
* Breakeven point = lower strike + net debit
* Theta plays important role in strike selection
* Risk reward gets skewed based on strike you choose.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Bull put spread :- 
* Difference in Bull Call spread in terms of strategy execution and strike selection.
* Bull put spread involved creating spread by ' Put option' rather than call option.
* Bull call spread is executed for debit, bull put spread executed for a credit.
* When to go with Bull Put spread
 1 - Markets have declined considerably
 2 - Volatility is on the higher side
 3 - Plenty of time to expiry 
* To implement
* Buy 1 OTM Put option
* Sell 1 OTM Put option
* What to ensure
 1- All strike belong to same underlying
 2- Belong to same expiry series
 3- each leg involve same number of options.
* Spread = Difference between higher and lower strike price
* Bull put spread max loss = spread - net credit
* Net credit = premium recieved for higher strike - paid for lower strike
* Bull put spread max profit = net credit
* Breakeven point = higher strike- net credit
* Higher the spread, higher the profit potential , higher the breakeven

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
Hey everyone! These are the learnings from **PHARUS** team (Chapter03) in the book"Identity is a good one.":
*Project: Rio cello (Rio Cello is a classical music event that invades the streets of Rio de Janeiro with art, music, and dance. The music repertoire promotes the encounter between classical and popular, with concerts of contemporary cello, choro, jazz, tango, and rock music.)*
The aim of this project was to connect musicians from around the world with the local population, for free.
THE BRIEF: There’s great importance in design planning, where the team map the present, in terms of competitors and benchmarks, and the future, in terms of trends and new aesthetic approaches.
PROJECT DELIVERABLES: Posters, banners, and identification badges, to the event schedule, DVD inlay cards, T-shirts, eco bags, bookmarks, Scotch tape, Havaianas sandals, etc. **Designers have an environmental responsibility that’s greater than most professions. ** (encourage green thinking)
TERMS AND CONDITIONS: Simply put terms and conditions (T&C) cover the deliverables, the number of potential rounds of modifications and people decided to the job, the project time frame, payment conditions, and cancellation terms. Sometimes, your terms are questioned, but remember queries are good because it means the terms have been read.
KNOWING WHAT TO CHARGE: Never change your work attitude based on the price of your proposal. Always give your absolute best. One needs to have two baskets: one holds the things you don’t give up, and the other holds what’s open to negotiation.
ESTIMATING THE PROJECT TIME FRAME: Knowing the team and understanding the internal processes make it easier to prepare estimates. You can’t have a one-month work attitude if the delivery is in a week. The Rio Cello project is one that had a pre-established deadline: the event opening day.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
PRO BONO RELATIONSHIP: Creative partnerships for pro bono design differ from those in more typical commercial work. Each party offers its specialized services for the better of the project. For the Rio Cello project, we had the freedom to conduct it in the way we considered most applicable. 
CONDUCTING RESEARCH: Belief in aesthetics with meaning works wonder, in a design that connects beauty and strategy, turning the intangible into reality. It’s important not to undersell your skills. For Rio Cello, team went to music concerts, interviewed musicians and participated in lecture on creativity by David to understand his passions, influences and motivations behind the event creation. They also searched for the musical textbooks to recognise and understand music’s visual codes. Every project is an opportunity to show your curiosity and increase your knowledge.
ON EXPERIMENTATION: Fundamental to innovation is the experience of experimenting. **The three main tools of any creative activity are a pencil, paper, and a trash can. **
THE PRESENTATION: They describe the concept, the process followed, and the insights generated from immersion in the subject behind the three creative paths they made. Sometimes ideas can be blunt and consistent, at this time, make a good design and present it with conviction. This builds confidence. Involving the client in your thought process before completing the presentation makes your paths likeable. **There’s no imposition of what we think we know about the client’s business. It’s something built together.  **
IDENTITY GUIDELINES: They should be inviting and constructive, and open enough to transverse an unpredictable future. It’s important to clarify the thinking behind an identity because this gives direction to its usage.
THE FIRST STEP TO FINDING CLIENTS: Before everything else, build and launch a consistent portfolio based on where you want to be positioned in the market and on the type of work you want to do more of.

Author: Mohit#0722
Content:
Anger — example
You did not fly into a rage and then start shouting. It is solely that you got angry so that you could shout. In other words, in order to fulfil the goal of shouting, you created the emotion of anger.

The goal of shouting came before anything else. That is to say, by shouting, you wanted to make the waiter submit to you and listen to what you had to say. As a means to do that, you fabricated the emotion of anger.

Anger is a tool that can be taken out as needed. It can be put away the moment the phone rings and pulled out again after one hangs up. The mother isn’t yelling in anger she can’t control. She is simply using the anger to overpower her daughter with a loud voice and thereby assert her opinions.

We are not controlled by emotion.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Bear call spread
* Invoked when view on market is moderately bearish.
* Bear call spread is similar to bear put spread in terms of payoff structure and different in terms of strategy execution and strike selection.
* Bear put is executed for debit, bear call spread for credit
* Points considered to choose
1- Markets have rallied considerably
2- Volatility is favorable 
3- Ample time to expiry
* Higher the spread, larger is profit potential.
* To implement
1- Buy 1 OTM call 
2- Sell 1 ITM call
* What to ensure
1- All strike belong to same underlying
2- belong to same expiry series
3- each leg involve same number of options
* Spread is difference between the strike price
* Net credit = premium recieved- premium paid
* Max profit = net credit
* Max loss = spread- net credit
* Effects of volatility
1- strategy doesn't vary much with increase in volatility when there is ample time to expiry.
2- cost to strategy varies moderately with increase of volatility when there is 15 days to expiry.
3- cost of strategy varies significantly with increase in volatility when there is about 5 days to expiry.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning
Bear put spread
* Spreads tend to shrink profitability but gives greater visibility on risk.
* It is equivalent to bull call spread.
* Would implement a bear put spread when market outlook is moderately bearish.
* Implementing bear put spread
1- Buy ITM put option
2- Buy OTM put option
* No compulsion that bear put spread has to be created with ITM and OTM option, can be created with any two put option.
* Both Options should belong to same expiry and same underlying.
* Strategy makes loss if spot moves above breakeven point and profit Below the breakeven point.
* Both profits and loss are capped.
* Spread is the difference between two strikes price
* Net debit = Premium paid- premium recieved
* Breakeven = higher strike- lower strike
* Max profit = spread - net debit
* Max loss = net debit
* Positive delta represent strategy is bullish.
* Delta neutral strategy are immune to market directional move, they react to changes in volatility and time, hence these are called " Volatility based strategies" .
* Effects of volatility
1- strategy doesn't vary much with increase in volatility when there is ample time to expiry.
2- cost to strategy varies moderately with increase of volatility when there is 15 days to expiry.
3- cost of strategy varies significantly with increase in volatility when there is about 5 days to expiry.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
The long straddle
* Simplest market neutral strategy to implement.
* After implantation P and L is not affected by direction of market movement.
* To implement
1- buy a call option
2- buy a put option
* Ensure
1- Both option belong to same underlying
2- both options Belong to same expiry
3- belong to same strike
* V shaped payoff curve
1- With reference to ATM strike, strategy makes money in either direction
2- Max loss is experienced when market don't move and stay at ATM.
Max loss = net premium paid
3- two breakeven
a) upper breakeven = ATM + net premium
b) lower breakeven = ATM- net premium
* Likely to double money in straddle provided
1- Set up straddle at the start of the month
2- Volatility at the time of setting up long straddle is relatively low
3- After setting up long straddle, the volatility doubles.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
ON CHOOSING A FINAL DIRECTION: While creating design options, personally you will have your own favourite, but you should present it equally with other options and then ask the client that “Where is your business going? Which one best aligns with your intent for the work you’re going to do in the next twenty years?” When choosing, clients should think about what their business needs are, not which system is “prettiest.” Believe in every idea you present so that whichever direction the client chooses, you’re in full agreement that it’s the right way forward
ON DESIGNING EXECUTION: The way to build the system for each client should take into account the way the system will be executed.
MEASURING THE SUCCESS OF A PROJECT: Success is also seeing the mission of the business aligning with the purpose of the identity—seeing a client’s business boosted by the redesign

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
Greetings to all! Here are some summarized content of Chapter04 of the book "Identity Designed is a Good one."
4.    **OCD**
Project: Ad Age *(Launched as a trade publication in the 1930s, Ad Age has become a global media brand with headquarters in New York City)*
THE CAPABILITIES PRESENTATION: Ad Age was interested in finding its digital voice, and wanting to work like a brand, not a trade publication. 
DELIVERABLES: Team was hired for the rebrand. **4 tools for proposals include research, strategy, design, and implementation.** 
THE CONTRACT: When you begin a relationship with the client, use broad strokes to outline the process, time line, and deliverables. After reaching an agreement, capture the details in a formal legal document. 
ON PRICING: Every pricing proposal is custom to the project. Sometimes it’s just to get the work and build your portfolio.
THE RESEARCH PHASE: Since Ad Age was launched in 1930, so it has an incredible collection of historical artifacts. Hence, team decided to estabilish patterns from history and create a design that familiarize client with their past moments rather than inventing a completely new style. 
THE STRATEGY PHASE: Strategy is about finding logic in our observations from the research phase and streamlining them into an inventory of challenges and opportunities for discussion. One need to understand what the business or product or organization is and then pick out the best parts and amplify them.
THE DESIGN PHASE: Design is a subjective solution, which is not necessarily one. You need to choose one that you think will work. Options offered to client are not fixed in number, options are generated when they speak in different voices. **The client makes a business decision rather than choosing a style. **

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning
Short straddle :- 
* Losses are uncapped.
* Just have to sell ATM call and put option.
* Options should belong to same underlying, same expiry and of same strike.
* Maximum profit occurs at ATM strike.
* Strategy remain profitable only between lower and higher breakdown.
* The losses are unlimited in either direction of market movement.
* Upper breakdown = ATM+ net premium
* Lower breakdown = ATM - net premium
* Short straddle works best when market are expected to be in a range and not really Expected to make large moves.
* This strategy is delta neutral
* Volatility should be high at time of strategy execution.
* Volatility should decrease during the holding period of strategy.

The long and short strangle
* Strangle is an improvisation over straddle, mainly to reduce cost implementation.
* Buy 1 OTM call and put option.
* Strangle is market neutral
* Both Options should belong to same underlying, same expiry.
* Execution should happen in same ratio.
* Few things to generalise
1- max loss is restricted to the net premium paid
2- loss would be maximum between the two strike.
3- upper breakeven point= CE strike+ net premium paid
4- lower breakeven point = PE strike - net premium paid
5- profit potential is unlimited
* Effects of Greek
* Volatility should be low at time of strategy execution
* Volatility should increase during holding period of strategy.
* Market should make large moves direction doesn't matter
* Expected move in time bound
* Short strangle
* Sell OTM call and put option
* Strategy results in loss when the market move in any direction.
* Strategy remain profitable, between lower and upper breakeven point.
* Payoff of short strangle looks exactly opposite of long straddle
* Profit are restricted to the extent of net premium recieved
* Profits are maximum as long as stock stays within the two strike price
* Losses are potentially unlimited.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
Hey everyone! Here's the summary of Chapter05 of the the book "Identity Designed is a Good one."
5.    **RICE CREATIVE**
Project: Rooster Beers *(Rooster Beers was founded in 2015 on a small piece of land in Can Gio, Vietnam. It began with a 150 liter (40 gallon)-fermentation system that was built from scratch, and a tiny, cold room to ferment the beer. Eighteen months later, their capacity had grown to 2,000 liters (528 gallons). They don’t use rice, sugar, cheap grain, or artificial flavors, and all their ingredients can be traced to origin.)*
In initial client meetings, team asked what the client was doing to make themselves stand out among the crowd and what their relevance was to the local market. The brand development and visual identity system can fall under phase one of a project. When that phase is completed, you’ll have a better idea of what applications will be needed in phase two, and then more phases can develop as your working relationship with the client continues. 
DELIVERABLES: This included research, brand strategy, design strategy, and the visual identity system, including identity guidelines.  
TERMS AND CONDITIONS: There is a need of solid contract structure to avoid needing to pursue legal action. Time division should be done wisely otherwise efficiency reduces. Also, sometimes there are delays from the client with their decision making or internal challenges. Individual contracts often need revisiting because a branding assignment is essentially a process of discovery.
WHEN CLIENTS QUERY THE TERMS: It’s easy to assume that our clients will understand our work. In the vast majority of cases, they do not. We have to carefully explain why it takes time to research. We have to explain that to make a website, we might have to hire a writer or photographer. “Third party costs may apply” always raises eyebrows.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
ON PRICING: **Try to separate your favorite brands from their visual identities. How would you evaluate that property in dollars? ** It’s all about the strategy that led to the identity—the thing that makes it all work. Getting involved and help to shape our clients’ businesses, is extremely valuable, so we keep that in mind when setting our fees.
WHEN TO INCREASE RATES: The author increases their rates every year due to inflation, increased overhead costs, etc. As soon as credibility increases to finished work, you could raise the rates and begin to educate the market. 
ON CLIENT NEGOTIATION: A reduction in budget for the same number of deliverables would result in us needing to bring in additional work to fill the gap.
ESTIMATING THE TIME FRAME: At the beginning, general time frame is proposed. But it never takes the exact time. 
INVOICING AND PAYMENT: For every payment, team issue an invoice. Payment schedule and scope of work are broken into milestone. For instance, after completing research one milestone is attained, etc.
THE RESEARCH PHASE: Looking for competition for beer makers doesn’t worked. So, team focused on client’s story, daily routine, vision and inspiration. A fantastic opportunity: they were the only one who make great, classic beers for the Vietnamese consumer. The competitors focussed on exotic ingredients. So, the focus was: simple, fresh range of beers for a local market. 
THE STRATEGY PHASE: Begins with questionnaire which is to be filled by client. Strategies are laid down that can focus creative work. **The concept that drives each design decision is what keeps the work strategic. **
GENERATING IDEAS: For Rooster three brand pillars: pridefulness, humor and substance were chosen and visual research for these terms was conducted.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
PRESENTING AN IDEA: Various platforms like Illustrator, Photoshop and InDesign are used in crafting presentations. The design direction is often already spelled out while presenting ideas for the verbal branding, positioning, and strategy, so while you have backup ideas in place, you should always share the main idea that we think best solves the problem.
ON COPYRIGHT AND TRADEMARKING: With law, there are guidelines, and then there are opinions. You should avoid risks and at the same time you should also be consious about too much of legal advice. 
DEVELOPING GUIDELINES: It’s good practice to think ahead, to leave aspects of the branding open for new adaptations. **We remind our clients to check with us when they’re unsure about implementation. **
ON STUDIO MARKETING: Investing time and effort in making your early projects as thoughtful proves fruitful. A happy client will bring you many more clients.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
Hey everyone! Here are some summarized notes of Chapter06
6.    **FOREIGN POLICY**
Project: Gallery & Co. *(Gallery & Co. is the official museum store at the National Gallery Singapore, with a bookstore, restaurant, bar, and design store in a continuous space. It fuses art and design into a curated retail experience offering books, design collectibles and prints, homeware, fashion, and children’s products, accompanied by the Gallery’s exclusive line of merchandise to complete the museum experience.) *
1.    Project involved interior design and space design, as well as merchandise design. Initial questions are generally same for all our identity projects, one crucial one is about their vision for the next five or ten years.
2.    When you’ve worked for at least a year, knowing how many projects you’ve accepted annually provides a good starting point to ascertain a rough range of how much revenue each project should yield. Multiply the number of projects you expect in the upcoming year by your estimated fee to give the desired annual income. Money isn’t the only thing you can earn. Skills can be traded for mutual benefit.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
3.    When team starts the project, type of research depends on looking at the market conditions and audit the competition and comparable offerings.
4.    Every brief must be bespoke. This is so because for example: if two clients say they want one, but what they truly want can be as different as day and night.
5.    Cutting through all the jargon, strategy is essentially about having a plan. When the plan is clear, the chances of success will be high.
6.    Generating ideas is easy: you’ll be surprised how solutions can so easily pop into your mind when they’re not forced.
7.    One should stop experimenting when they’re happy with what we have and when the client’s happy with what’s presented.
8.    It’s practically impossible to create something that bears no resemblance to another design.
9.    During presentation, remember number of ideas don’t matter: **It’s not about quantity, but about that one killer bullet. **Only present ideas that you’re comfortable with.
10.    Your guidelines need to be fairly prescriptive because a brand cannot be ambiguous or subjected to different interpretations. Decide well in advance which items are cast in stone and which have a degree of flexibility.
11.    Also ask how clients think design will help them, as their answers will give you an understanding of their design knowledge. When you work with people who don’t appreciate or value design, the process becomes a very difficult battle to win

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of jc hull (Bible) chapter 1 :- 
Derivatives :- 
Financial instrument whose value depends on the value of some other, more basic, underlying variable.
Q-) Why didn't put underlying asset why we are putting underlying variable?
A-) It doesn't necessarily have to be an asset it could be a real asset like property or financial asset like share of stocks or index or could be an event. Ex - amount of snowfall at certain region.  or cat event which only pays off when capestrophe happen.
Derivatives are of two derivatives
1- Exchange traded 
* Standardized contact
* Highly regulated
* Reduce counterparty risk
2- over the counter
* Can be standardized but they allow lot of customisation
* Between buyer and seller, also called bilateral clearing
* Now a days involve clearing party to overcome counterparty risk
Dollar value wise OTC are twelve Times larger than exchange traded. In terms of market value exchange traded is larger.
Forwards :- 
Agreement to buy or sell a specific asset at a specific price at a certain future date.
* It is OTC traded
* Buyer and seller both are obligated.
* No money change hands
If a forward is exchange traded is called future contact.
On future there will be margin but margin doesn't leave your account, during contract.
Derivatives are zero sum game.
No wealth is created in derivatives contact .
Payoff graphs for buyers and sellers are mirror image.
Options :- 
Call 
1-) buyer ---- right ----to buy
2-) seller ---- obligated---- to sell
Put 
1-) buyer ---- right----- to sell
2-) seller ---- obligated----- to buy
Option are traded at a specific price (strike or exercise) and at specific time (expiration )of a specific underlying.
American option :- anytime exercise
European option :- last day exercise
Premium Change hands---- buyers pay the seller
From European option you can quit trade anytime.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Types of traders :- 
1-) hedgers :-
Use derivatives to reduce risk.
2-) speculators :- 
Take on risk, make a price bet.
3-) Arbitrageous :- 
Make riskless profit, take advantage of mispriced assets .

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of chapter : 2
Mechanics of future market
Contract size :- depends on the asset
Each contract have different size depending on asset.
Mini's are also there . Like contract size of natural gas is 6000 Mbtu but mini is around 2500 , even CG size is 10000 ounce but mini is 10 ounces
As we move in Mini contract there is less liquidity, usually wide spread between bid and ask.
Delivery specifications :-
Buyers or sellers do not choose it. It is already set. EX - Corn is delivered at Toledo , Oil West Intermediation at Cushing Oklahoma. You must manage and pay from there to your location.
Month of contract doesn't mean contract expiration. Ex :- Oil October contact will be expired around September mid.17 is the tentative date seen a lot but it might be from 15-19 depending whether sunday or Saturday is on 17. cattle, live cattle for August means it will expire around 25 August. So in case of oil you are making a bet on October price but im real you are making bet on September price at that time not in October.
Oil, natural gas trades all months and they are delivered every month.
Corn,wheat, soyabean are traded in March,may,july,september, December months only. Because it follows harvest schedule, winter wheat vs summer wheat, new supply vs old supply.
Daily price limit:- 
All the future contract reduce volatility in these markets have price limit. Means the most it can go up or down in a day. If reaches max limit it is called limit up and if drops maximum by the daily price limit it is limit down.
No trade occurs outside these limits.trading is halted above these doesn't mean trade is off for the entire day.
Position limit :- 
Maximum number of contract an individual can hold.
Margin requirements :- 
Marked to market ( daily settlement) is done in future contact.
Both seller and buyer holds X amount of margin in their account no money change on the contract formation. 75% of this margin is maintaince margin below which one gets margin call to make again X .

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Depending upon the price movement margin amount is deducted from buyer or seller account at the end of the day.
* Margins call must be met by contract close that day.
* Initial margin need not to be cash.
Treasure :- around 90% of treasury worth can be used as margin
Stocks :- around 50-70% value of that stocks can be used as margins
Credit risk is almost zero(not in every case)
OTC :- customisable not marked to market.
* Last day settlement
* Counterparty risk
Trades having sufficient liquidity and standardized can move to central party involvement.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
Greetings to all! Here are the summarized points of chapter07:
7.    **UNDERLINE STUDIO**
Project: Art Museum *(Art Museum at the University of Toronto is a new institution that brings the Justina M. Barnicke Gallery and the University of Toronto Art Centre together as one entity. It’s one of the largest gallery spaces in Toronto for visual art exhibitions and programming.) *
1.    Initial question asked was that what they want us to deliver in direction of design. For Art Museum, much of the discussion focused on how they were situated within the university. How they were going to create their own unique identity within 2 galleries in 2 different colleges was a big question.
2.    Art Museum hired us to design the brand identity (including guidelines, signage, a brochure template, stationery package, the website design and development, etc). Signage was a critical part of the project. (Since, visitors find it difficult to find way)
3.    Don’t release any final files to the client until payment has been received. **Having a colleague deal with clients on billing allows our designers to focus on design. ** 
4.    Working terms has sections for fees, cancellation procedure, copyright ownership, changes and approvals, confidential information, as well as samples and promotional ability. Payment schedule: 35 percent deposit to begin work, 35 percent at delivery, and 30 percent within thirty days of delivery.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
5.    Approximation of hours and trying to account for all the tasks of the project: research, design, meetings, press approvals, changes, and so on helps in knowing what to charge. 
6.    When a client hasn’t gone through an in-depth strategic process (with interviews, SWOT analyses, and so on) and it’s clear that one is necessary, you need to collaborate with an external strategy partner.
7.    The design phase: While exploring designs, one need to consider the designs of competitor’s logo. The color palette is a big part of the identity’s success. 
8.    It’s important to show how the identity will perform in a variety of contexts. One should not tell clients which idea we prefer so as not to influence them one way or another. This is done to take their feedback and to gauge their reactions. Try to present the concepts in the context of the original strategy. Referring the client back to the brief is always our first method in taking away the subjective element.
9.    Constraints don’t last when the identity could now achieve what the client wanted. 
10.    For complete brand identity guidelines outline the visual elements of the brand as well as their usage. **How the branding will be implemented and carried forward can influence our creative decisions. ** For a design to be successful, the effort required in its application and rollout must be realistic for the company that’s using it.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning
Market quotes :- prices per unit are mentioned
Open price :- the price at which the stock was started trading at a day
High price :- the highest price of that trading day.
Low price :- the lowest price of that trading day.
Close price :- settlement price used for daily settlement.
Depending on the contract settlement price and time varies.for grain it is 2:15 pm price is the settlement price it doesn't mean trading is done at that point, it might be traded till 5:15 but the closing price will be of 2:15 only .
Similarly for energy 2:30 pm price will be the settlement Price.
Trading volume:- it is number of contract traded in a day.
Open interest :- it is as of closing how many contacts are still in existence.
Delivery :- very few contract leads to delivery.
Usually closed out - speculators,hedgers
Delivery can be expensive.
Time period of delivery is set up by option writer and date of delivery is also decided by him only.
Notice of intention
* No of contract
* Location
* Grade
Exchange :- chase party with long position ( usually oldest outstanding position)
Cash settlement :- * most financial future. i.e, S$P 500.
Whenever we opt for fraction of shares it is impossible to deliver them and that types are then cash settled.
Order types :- 
Market :-  It means you're gonna buy it whenever the price is or sell whatever the price is, buy on the offer and sell on the bid.
Limit :- you specify the price.
Whenever we trade in future the default price will be the limit is highly recommended in derivatives to specify your price rather than taking a chance.
Stop :- stop is a modifier that we place on an order either stop or stop loss, buy stop is when you are short you want to buy to close so you have a stop saying if price goes above this you want to stop.
Regulation :- future market regulated by commodity futures trading commission. Dodd frank act expands CFTC oversight to OTC markets.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
Hey everyone! Here's the summary of chapter08:
8.    **FEDORIV**
Project: Rezult *(Korosten MDF Plant in Ukraine is an environmentally friendly factory producing laminate flooring and medium-density fiberboard (MDF) panels. Equipped with cutting-edge Siempelkamp machinery, the plant operates large storage facilities, a traffic network, and its own utility systems. It stands among the top-ranked Ukrainian companies that used to export its products to Russia, benefiting from its favorable location near a major southeastern railway hub (Korosten, in the Zhytomyr region).) *
1.    With branding and positioning projects, discussions should always be at the CEO level. From an identity viewpoint, if a client focuses on the rational benefits, the designer tends to think the project will be dull and unattractive, preferring to work on something that incites more passion. When trying to achieve consensus in traditional corporate structures, there are too many people with the authority to say no, but not many that can say yes.
2.    Rethinking a brand includes two phases. The first phase in a change project is critical, when we take a “deep dive” into the client’s business to understand their brand, market, consumer, environment, positioning, and vision. **Change will come in three years, after months of understanding what you want to change. ** The second area one needs to deliver is branding. For branding, working on positioning, identity design, and communication is done. 
3.    Client negotiation can be applied to the number of elements you develop. Never sell something that doesn’t match your methodology even if your client insists because it can negatively influence the final result. **Don’t touch a project unless you believe you can do great things. ** Choosing the clients, you like and the projects you believe in is the only way to build a business.

Author: sparkling#3483
Content:
4.    With Rezult, it wasn’t necessary to carry out research into consumer behavior. Team interviewed managers from their retail partners to understand what they wanted, and then let them judge the prototypes. The process needs a trusting client who can give enough time for concept development.
5.    Changing our mental nationality is a very productive creative tool. The use of a cutting theme in the project was insisted inspired from the working with wood. When the projects involve brand naming, one need to present five to seven names.
6.    There were two main presentations for Rezult—the naming and the design. During naming, mood and emotional territory of each option was presented and illustration of them with various references was made. For design presentation, it’s important to focus on one or two directions. When it’s two, we make them radically different. Content:
Hey everyone! Here's the summary of chapter09:
9.    **FREYTAG ANDERSON**
Project: Frayher Architects *(Fraher is an award-winning architectural practice in London, with the ability to analyze, conceptualize, design, produce, and deliver spaces and architecture in a fully integrated package.)*
1.    When a potential client approaches, a briefing sheet is given to them as it acts as a stimulus, challenging clients to really think about what they want. One merit of being a designer is that you always learn more about the client's industry.
2.    When you realize that project is a good fit for you, one needs to prepare a proposal which is a document that sets out the context and parameters of the project in a digestible way, giving clarity to costs and time frames.  
3.    Every project should be given the same level of importance, regardless of budget. 
4.    Setting up your own terms and conditions not only protect your intellectual property but more importantly they tell a valued client your ideas and processes and that you are willing to uphold them. 
5.    Sometimes, A project that provides an opportunity to reach a new market, can be more important than a higher-paying one.  **The best and most successful projects are those where the client feels they have mutual ownership.  **
6.    The best strategy to design is to get to know the client, what they do, how they do it and, perhaps most important, why. When it comes to merging strategy with design, interpreting brand values, traits, and positioning in a visual sense is an instinctive part of every designer’s job. The written voice for a brand comes naturally, in the same way. 
7.    It’s important to fully develop an idea, test it, and make sure it’s both evocative and practical. **If you can rationalize your ideas, and provide sound business reasons for design choices, clients will listen. Don’t be afraid to say no, but tell them why.**  Explain approaches clearly, in layperson terms.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning
Chapter :- 3
Hedging with future
Aim :- to reduce the risk of exposure
When we hedge with future, we ignore daily settlement 
Short hedge
Let's assume company A have exposure to asset B .
* If price of B increase , it's great but when it decreases it's not good.
To neutralize this position let's short future on B
So as price of B increase, future price will decrease and vice versa
And addition of these two will result to neutralize each other's loss and gain.
Example :- company A will sell 1 million barrels of oil at August 15 at whatever the spot price is . As we know that oil contract expires one month earlier if we made August contract it would have expired on around 17 july and we would have faced basis risk. So to avoid this we should have chosen September contact.
If today's spot price is $79 and on August 15 it is $85 , buyer is gonna lose $6 but if price is $ 75 seller is gonna lose $4 . So to hedge the risk we can short a future along with it.
Note :- hedging reduce risk and also reduce the chances of getting reward. It's upto us to chose between limited risk and limited reward or unprotected position with chance of reward.
Long hedge :-
Company B needs to purchase asset C.
* If price of C increase it's not good but if price of C decrease it's great
But as we have risk associated with we can just buy future on C.
As price of C increase future price of C increase and vice versa.
So these two positions will neutralize each other's risk.
Ex :- Company needs to purchase 10000 lbs of copper may.
Since copper expires on the same month but the closure will be around 15 may but expiration date will be around last week of may.so likewise  months can be chosen to counter this basis risk.
As we have discussed the opposite movement of future long and the asset C we can neutralize our position.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Stock index futures :- 
* Cash settled
* Marked to market or daily settlement
There are two types of indices 
* Price weighted (DOW)
* Market cap weighted (S&P 500) mostly traded on this
Index pairs trade :- 
Long strong/ short weak
Long strong portfolio :- when market moves up .
Portfolio increase more than the movement in index and the difference is our profit
When market moves down :- portfolio decrease less than the decrement in index and difference is our profit.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning
Chapter 3
Basis risk :- 
1-) using a proxy Futures for an asset
The asset that you want to hedge doesn't have a future contract so you can use a future contract with an underlying asset that is close to the asset you are using.
2-) Asset purchase/ sale date vs contact expiration
Convergence on the last day of trading for that future have to lose your future contract out before the expiration date or when they won't converge which means you'll have gap between two price, called basis risk
3-) Risk of delivery/ expiration overlap
Until and unless you don't choose a future exactly same as your asset and your expiration date is exactly same as delivery date you are always going to have basis risk
Basis = $ spot price of asset to be hedged- $ future contract used
Basis (spread) 
* Can increase over time - strengthening
* Can decrease over time - weakening
Short hedge & positive basis = better case
Short hedge & negative basis = worse case
Long hedge & positive basis = worse case
Long  hedge & negative basis = better case
Hedge ratio :- size of position in future by size of exposure
Cross hedging :- 
When the asset that you have exposure to does not have a future contract and you have to use another asset underlying the future contract and you have to use another asset underlying the future contract to hedge out that's called cross hedging and that hedge will be affected by the correlation between Target asset and future asset
To find hedge ratio or to perfectly hedge our position with cross hedging
We need series of change in spot price and change in future price
When plotting these two values the slope gives us hedge ratio
Plot of variance of position
What is position :- position is the difference between asset price and h* times future price.
We select h such that variance is minimum implying minimum risk.
Optimal number of contract = h* times quantity of asset to be hedged by size of 1 future contract

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Revision
Interest rate :- the return obtained from an investment without risk. It is important because act as benchmark to make assesment about other possible investment
Ex :- pure discount bond 
Compute interest rate :- 
R be the interest rate P(T) = amount after t time
P(0) = amout at t = 0
P(T)= P(0)(1+r)
This is single period model
If r is quarterly rate A= (1+4r) for 1 rupee investment return in 1 year in simple interest
If r is quarterly rate A = (1+r)^4 for 1 rupee investment in 1 year in compound interest
Continuous compounding
Present value :- 
Requirement is to make a choice between two future casflows of several payment
Idea is to use technique of interest calculation in opposite direction
When we take a loan and pay m installments it is called loan is ammoltized over m periods.

Author: asdgr8#1422
Content:
Time flies. And it literally does when you are in college. That is the biggest problem I have faced in my college life.  When you have personality of an explorer, a dreamer, you have to manage your time very precisely or else your exploration will never reach any milestones. I know that many of you might be facing this problem of time management. I will recommend a wonderful trick that can change your life and believe me when I say this because I have tried tens of things in past 2.5 years and only this worked. buy a simple smartwatch, which will cost around 1500, don't worry it's investment on yourself. Now download and application like Google tasks where you can schedule your targets and get notified on your watch with a little vibration throughout the day. This way even if you are not able to complete your tasks with an efficiency of 100% your subconscious mind will at least get to know that these things are to be done.

 If not today, you will do it tomorrow but you will definitely do that task and the task will not get disappeared in that flying time.

Author: asdgr8#1422
Content: My biggest trigger was fear of failing. But I think after a point of time you realise, if you are sitting idle fearing failure, you have failed already. And as soon as this realisation came in, things started looking clearer, dreams started looking nearer!
